<HEADLINE> G.P. Koirala Named New PM of Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Girija Prasad Koirala,
president and parliamentary leader of the Nepali Congress (NC),
was appointed as new prime minister of the Himalayan kingdom
Sunday by King Birendra, said a communique issued by the king's
Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Surya Bahadur Thapa resigned last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new appointment was made as no submission was received in
response to the king's call for any member of the lower house of
parliament, who can establish one's majority in the house with the
support of two or more parties, to stake a claim to power, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
A simple majority of 103 votes is needed in the 205-seat House
to form a government.
</P>
<P>
The king had set 6:00 p.m. Sunday as the deadline. But the NC
could not find a ruling partner as the talks between it and other
parties on formation of a coalition government failed over
allocation of portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, in the event that a coalition
government is not available, the king may ask a member of the
largest party in the House to form a government.
</P>
<P>
Coalition politics emerged in the Himalayan kingdom after the
mid-term polls in November 1994 produced a hung parliament where
no single party holds a majority.
</P>
<P>
But the NC, the largest party in the House with 87 MPs, has
decided to form a minority government on its own strength.
</P>
<P>
However, the move was called a "suicidal game" by a minister of
the care-taker government.
</P>
<P>
The minority government led by Man Mohan Adhikari of the
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) three
years ago lasted only 10 months.
</P>
<P>
And as the general elections are due by November 1999, the
scramble for power is expected to become more tense.
</P>
<P>
Surya Bahadur Thapa resigned to make way for the NC, one of his
ruling partners, to head a new government under an agreement he
had reached before he took office last October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
