<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Syria to Coordinate Stances on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Transportation Minister
Umar Miskawi said on Sunday that Lebanese and Syrian leaders will
coordinate stances on the Israeli offer to withdraw from south
Lebanon, the Voice of Arab Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese-Syrian summit comes within the context of
coordination vis-a-vis Israel's recent offer on conditional
implementation of the United Nations Security Council Resolution
425," Miskawi told the Cairo-based Arabic-language radio.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and his Lebanese counterpart
Elias Hrawi will meet on Monday in Syria's Latakia to scrutinize
the Israeli proposal.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to accept the U.N. resolution 425,
which demands an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
But it meanwhile insisted that security arrangements for border
areas be worked out with Lebanese government before any pullout
can be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate their positions on
all key issues, have rejected Israel's offer, insisting that
Israel withdraw unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
"This refusal does not contradict Lebanese endeavor to achieve
peace and stability in the region," Miskawi told. He called on the
United States to seriously consider Lebanon's clear-cut attitude.
</P>
<P>
Beirut was asked by the U.S. to thoroughly study the Israeli
offer. On Friday, Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz received
a message to this effect from U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
According to the Egyptian Al Ahram daily newspaper, Albright in
the message stressed that Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai "seriously" wished to pull out the forces from south
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
