<HEADLINE> Round-up:  Carlsen, First Dane to Win ATP Tour Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An expectedly long and grueling
battle came out to end in just 72 minutes -- that was the case for
the men's singles final at the 340,000 U.S. dollars Salem Open
Hong Kong tennis tournament here on Sunday, with Danmark's eighth
seed Kenneth Carlsen outscoring Zimbabwe's Byron Black to take the
title.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, 76th-ranked Carlsen became the first Dane to
win an ATP Tour title. He turned professional in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Left-handed Carlsen, 24, overwhelmed Black 6-2, 6-0 in the
final which was interrupted by rain time and again, from Sunday
afternoon to the evening. The two had split honors in their six
previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
The 1.90-meter-tall Carlsen broke Black's first service game in
the opening set before there came a waiting game for more than
three hours due to the rain.
</P>
<P>
But it was Carlsen's explosive serving and steady baseline play
that worked so well to bring him to the triumph.
</P>
<P>
Black, Zimbabwe's hero who downed U.S. Open champion Pat Rafter
in Zimbabwe's Davis Cup win last week over Australia, felt it hard
to find the consistent double-handed backhand and forehand game
which had helped him to defeat in the final Brazil's French Open
champion Gustavo Kuerten in last October's Marlboro championship
here.
</P>
<P>
Black had been ousted in the first round in both of his
previous appearances in the Salem Open, in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
"It's unbelievable to become the first Dane to win a title on
the ATP Tour -- I have been waiting for a title for many years and
I am glad I have finally done it," said Carlsen.
</P>
<P>
He owed the victory to his "unbelievable rhythm". "During the
rain break I just read a book and tried to relax - it seemed to
have worked," he added.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded Black, ranked 81st in ATP Tour, had made hard efforts
during the week-long tournament and looked tired and out of shape
in the title clash.
</P>
<P>
Carlsen, a left-hander and the only seed of the tournament to
survive for the final, said the victory was "unbelievable".
</P>
<P>
"I have been waiting to win a title for many years. I'm glad I
have
eventually done it...I had unbelievable rhythm today," he added.
</P>
<P>
Carlsen, who was to celebrate his 25th birthday five days
later, said he had tried to stay focused during a four-hour break
caused by steady rain between the first and second games of the
first set.
</P>
<P>
Reading and some sleep helped him to stay focused. "It worked
well," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Carlsen, who was to celebrate his
25th
birthday five days later, had advanced to the final of the Salem
Open
after three appearances.
</P>
<P>
Later Sunday, Black teamed up with American Alex O'Brien to
beat Neville Godwin from South Africa and Tuomas Ketola of Finland
7-5, 6-1 and won the men's doubles title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
