<HEADLINE> Home for Angolan War Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- 10 kilometers east of the
Angola's capital city, on the side of the highway is a courtyard
enclosed by yellow walls. Under the green trees are rows of
houses, clean and peaceful. Here is Palanca Orphans' Home.
</P>
<P>
In order to see how the children are living now, the
correspondent of Xinhua News Agency recently paid a visit to the
orphanage.
</P>
<P>
There are now 220 children aged from six to eighteen living
here. They have come from 12 provinces, including Luanda,
Malanje, Zaire, Kuanza-sul, Moxico, Huambo, Bie and Benguela.
</P>
<P>
The dormitories in which these children live are both spacious
and bright. There are four double-berth beds in each room and
the beddings are orderly arranged. In the yard, several children
are playing merrily.
</P>
<P>
The dining room and the kitchen are just around the corner.
Inside the dining room, tables and chairs are put in good order.
Great attention has been paid to the sanitation in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
According to the coordinator of the center, Antonio Julho, who
accompanied the visiting correspondent, Palanca Orphans' Home was
initiated by some 20 teachers in Luanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the end of 1992, civil war broke out again in Angola after
only one year of ceasefire. The fierce fighting lasted for about
one year, leaving 500,000 dead and more than 70,000 orphaned.
These children who had been deprived of their families in the war
began to wander in the streets with scare food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
In order to help these street children, Palanca Orphans' Home
was soon established with the help of the society and some
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program provides food; Africare, a
non-governmental organization, provides fund for education; while
the Angolan state-owned power plants and water works provide
electricity and water, all free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Julho said that the authorities of the Home had tried their
best to provide enough food for children. Now, three meals with
adequate nourishment are guaranteed. Rice, flour, beans, meat,
fish, chicken, butter, milk are among the staples in Palanca.
</P>
<P>
Besides the general courses provided in ordinary elementary
schools, Palanca also arranges some special classes for children
living there, teaching them skills of carpentry, blacksmith,
tailoring and typing. With such vocational education, Palanca
children can master a kind of skill so that they can live by
themselves after they step into the society.
</P>
<P>
Following the guidance of their teachers, children are working
attentively in their practices. Despite the muggy weather,
children are fully devoted to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
One important issue is how to find jobs for the orphans after
they grow up. In 1997 alone, almost 100 orphans found places in
the Angolan armed forces, the national police and other
government sectors, having reliable financial resources. In such
a war-torn country as Angola where unemployment rate is very
high, it can be regarded as a miracle for the orphans to secure
jobs.
</P>
<P>
When Palanca Home first opened, 600 orphans were invited to
live there. But these children who were born and grew in wars
had been used to their free life. Many left, unable to bear the
strict disciplines and schedule at the Home.
</P>
<P>
In order to make these children live here, teachers in Palanca
have drained their brains. They first managed to improve the
diet for the children despite all difficulties. And they also
bought table tennis, footballs and basketballs and organized
sports games. Children in Palanca gradually got accustomed to
the disciplines and timetables they previously could not stand.
</P>
<P>
At first when the Orphans' Home was established, teachers in
Palanca had no pay. They began to receive some subsidies only
after 1996. However, Julho said, they chose to do so in order to
reduce the pains the orphans are suffering and help the country
overcome difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Many orphans are hurt psychologically. Some of them had been
child soldiers themselves and some had seen their parents killed
before their eyes. Wars had broken their hearts.
</P>
<P>
Palanca sent teachers to study psychology at the seminars
lectured by foreign experts. They have greatly relieved the
mental burdens of these war orphans.
</P>
<P>
One child named Antonio with passion told the reporter that he
and his pals love their home in Palanca. While well fed and well
clothed, they can also obtain knowledge there, said Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
