<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sends Condolences to Saudi Stampede </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Foreign
Affairs Department Sunday sent its condolences to the bereaved
families of those who died in the Hajj stampede near Mecca in
Saudi Arabia Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At least 118 people were killed when Moslem pilgrims swept
over hundreds of mostly elderly people on the last day of the
annual pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
"Having had one death and a few injuries amongst the South
African pilgrims, we share the profound grief and sorrow with the
families from other parts of the world who have lost their loved
ones during the tragic incident," the department said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Four Pakistanis, two Saudis, one Indian, three unidentified
persons and the driver and his son plus a man from
Pietermaritzburg, South Africa, were reportedly killed in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
"We also pray for the speedy recovery and good health to those
who were injured during the incident," the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
