<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: New Nepali Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Girija Prasad Koirala,
president and parliamentary leader of the Nepali Congress, was
appointed Sunday by King Birendra as new prime minister of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
For the 73-year-old Koirala, the premiership is nothing new. He
took office in May 1991 as the Himalayan kingdom's first popularly
elected prime minister in 30 years. And his brothers Matrika
Prasad Koirala and Bishweshwar Prasad Koirala were also prime
ministers of Nepal in the 1950s and early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
G.P. Koirala began his political career while working at a jute
mill in Biratnagar of eastern Nepal. He participated in the first
industrial strike held in the mill in 1947.
</P>
<P>
He led the labor movement in Biratnagar after the dissolution
of multi-party system in Nepal in 1960, and in the same year he
was arrested and jailed under the State Offense Act for seven
years. He went on a hunger strike in jail for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Three years after he was released from jail, G.P. Koirala was
arrested again under the Security Act. Later he exiled himself to
India until 1979.
</P>
<P>
G.P. Koirala held the post of youth leader of the NC for many
years. In 1976, he was elected the party's general secretary at a
party conference held in India.
</P>
<P>
His active involvement in the armed struggle against the
partyless Panchayat system which was in place for three decades
culminated in the people's movement in February 1990 launched by
his party and the communists.
</P>
<P>
The movement forced King Birendra to abolish the Panchayat
system and introduce a multi-party democratic system in the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the first free elections in May 1991, G.P. Koirala was
elected a member of the House of Representatives, and his party
won a clear majority. He assumed the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In March 1994, he resigned and recommended mid-term polls after
losing a key vote in parliament. The polls in November 1994
resulted in a hung parliament where no single party held a
majority, which led to the emergence of coalition politics in
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
But G.P. Koirala was reelected a member of the lower house of
parliament in the November 1994 elections. And in May 1996, he was
elected president of the NC at the 9th general convention of the
party.
</P>
<P>
The rangy, bespectacled new prime minister believes in "nation,
nationalism and democratic socialism advocated by NC," and
"dedication to duty, firmness in devotion and commitment to
stabilize democracy."
</P>
<P>
He remains single after his wife died many years ago. He has
one daughter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-12 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Supports U.N. Efforts to End Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Sunday reiterated that Iran fully supports efforts of
the United Nations to solve the crisis in Afghanistan, the
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's
special envoy on Afghan affairs Lakhdar Brahimi, Khatami said all
the neighbors and regional states should help the U.N. and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) with efforts to bring
the Afghan crisis to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran is highly concerned with the deplorable
conditions of the oppressed Afghan people, especially women and
children who are denied their most basic rights in the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, also the OIC chairman, stressed that the Afghan
crisis could not be resolved militarily, adding that the OIC is
fully prepared to help settle the issue peacefully.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Brahimi delivered to Khatami a message from
Annan saying that the U.N. hopes to put an end to the Afghan
crisis through cooperation with the OIC and Afghanistan's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He briefed Khatami on his talks with senior officials of
Turkmenistan, Pakistan, Uzbekistan and Afghanistan over the issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special envoy arrived here Saturday from Islamabad,
Pakistan, to consult with Iranian officials on the Afghan issue
after concluding his visits to Afghanistan and several central
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on
Sunday to underline the need for peace talks among all the
belligerent groups in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said that agreements between Afghan neighbors can help
remove the obstacles in the process.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that Iran believes that negotiations are the only
alternative to achieve peace and tranquillity in Afghanistan, and
that the U.N. and the OIC will undoubtedly take positive steps
towards establishing peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation among the regional countries will also accelerate
the settlement of the crisis, he added. 
</P>
