<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Sentence Turkish Ship Captain, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian State Security Court
Sunday sentenced both the owner and captain of a Turkish ship to
15 years in prison for kidnaping and piracy, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Naci Usakli, captain of the Turkish cargo vessel Obo Engin and
Helmi Adelair, its owner, were tried in absentia. It is now known
if and how the sentence will be enforced.
</P>
<P>
On October 23, 1997, the ship defied an Egyptian court order in
connection with its default of 375,000 U.S. dollars in transit
tolls to the Suez Canal Authority.
</P>
<P>
The captain had refused orders to hand over the ship and took
hostage the Egyptian officials who embarked it to make good on a
court order for its seizure. The ship was carrying 40,000 tonnes
of coal from Singapore.
</P>
<P>
According to the eight Egyptians - a court official, two port
police, two lawyers, two shipping agents and a canal official,
they were confined to four cabins when the ship fled back to
Istanbul, the largest port city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
They were threatened to be thrown overboard if they caused
troubles.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling described both the piracy and abduction as
"acts unprecedented" in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
