traditional parade peacefully in Belfast, Northern Ireland, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The march, organized and participated by the Apprentice Boys,
was held to mark their past victories over Roman Catholics and
show their loyalty to the British government.
</P>
<P>
The streets resounded to the sound of drums, pipes and singing
from an array of colorful bands on the first day of the "marching
season", a focus for violence in the past.
</P>
<P>
The march stopped shot of the mainly Catholic Lower Ormeau Road
in south Belfast after a new parades commission had banned the
marchers from proceeding down the street to avoid rioting.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the same parade -- the first contentious event
of the marching season -- led to serious rioting and several dead.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman in Northern Ireland hailed the peaceful
completion of the parade, saying the Protestants has shown "a high
degree of integrity."
</P>
<P>
The march was held three days after the political parties
involved in the Northern Ireland conflict reached a historic peace
agreement which many say would usher in a new era for the divided
province. 
