<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Emphasizes Management of Underground Water Resources (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China, one of 13 countries facing
serious water shortages, will formulate a plan later this year
to scientifically develop underground water resources, according
to the Ministry of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
Detailed management measures will be adopted in the interim,
according to a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that only 290 billion out of China's 870
billion cu.m. underground water resources are available for
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
China has over 3.45 million wells where some 90 billion cubic
meters of underground water reserves are exploited annually, the
third largest underground water user following the United States
and India.
</P>
<P>
In the 1960s, underground water were exploited in a few large
cities such as Shanghai, Beijing and Tianjin. However, the
situation changed dramatically along with rapid economic
development in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The overuse of underground water has created a series of
problems such as lowering of water table and expediting
environmental deterioration, according to Liu Yingqiu, an expert
from the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
She also pointed to equally serious problems such as shortages
and contamination of underground water.
</P>
<P>
Overuse in coastal cities such as Dalian, Qinhuangdao and Yantai
have resulted salt water leeching into underground water tables
and further problems resulting from the increasing salinization of
cultivatable land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
