<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Destroy 224,000 Hectares of Forest in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Fires raging out of control in
East Kalimantan province, Indonesia, have destroyed more than
224,000 hectares of forests since the beginning of this year, a
local official said.
</P>
<P>
At least 224,384 hectares of forests in the drought-stricken
province have been destroyed by the fires, local newspapers Monday
quoted Awang Faruk Ishak, head of East Kalimantan's Environmental
Impact Control Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 198,000-hectare Kutai National Park, the province's largest
natural forest park, is one of the hardest hit, with close to 36
percent of cover destroyed as of April 8, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Fires have also swept through 55,463 hectares of forest
concessions, 66,839 hectares of timber estate and close to 3,000
hectares of plantations, Ishak said.
</P>
<P>
He put losses at more than 4.817 trillion rupiah (595 million
U.S. dollars), not counting the cost of environmental and health
damage.
</P>
<P>
Ishak said thousands of fires continued to burn in the province
despite efforts to curb their advance.
</P>
<P>
The lack of rain since the middle of last year has left forest
and ground cover extremely susceptible to fires, he added.
</P>
<P>
Water bombing, artificial rain-making and military support to
local fire-fighters have failed to put out the fires, Ishak said.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a repeat of the haze in Southeast Asia last year, when
smoke from Indonesian fires blanketed much of the region and
caused widespread health problems and transport disruption, were
eased by strong winds helping to dissipate the haze.
</P>
<P>
But the smoke has made thousands ill in East Kalimantan and led
to shortages of food and water in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than 300,000 hectares of forests were destroyed
by fires in Sumatra and Kalimantan islands in Indonesia, causing
at least 3 billion dollars of losses to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
