<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Asia Financial Turmoil Abates, Global Slowdown Mild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The financial turmoil in Asia
which erupted in mid-1997 has abated since January and the
projected global economic slowdown is mild, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Confidence is gradually recovering during this year and a
moderate growth should be expected next year in the crisis-struck
Asian countries, said IMF in a report called World Economic
Outlook.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the threat to global growth from the crisis in
Asia appears to be limited, the report projected world output
growth in 1998 at just over 3.1 percent and 3.7 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
It said that the affected countries have implemented corrective
measures while the international community led by the IMF has
provided financial support for policy programs in Indonesia, Korea
and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
While uncertainties have persisted in Indonesia, it is clear
that elsewhere commitments to implement the necessary reforms and
adjustment measures have strengthened substantially, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Markets have partially recovered from their troughs, it
affirmed.
</P>
<P>
"As the needed policies are implemented and external positions
improve, confidence should recover gradually during 1998, paving
the way for a moderate rebound in growth in 1999 and solid
recovery by 2000," it said.
</P>
<P>
The particular severity and importance of financial sector and
other structural weaknesses in the Asian crisis mean that the
necessary corrective measures may take longer to implement than in
crises that can be resolved mainly by macroeconomic adjustment, it
added.
</P>
<P>
"But at the same time the deep declines that have occurred in
currency and financial markets suggest scope for relatively sharp
rebounds as confidence recovers," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that currency and asset values in the countries
struck by the crisis have been left far below levels before the
crisis, the report said considerable uncertainty remains about the
resolution of the crisis and its global repercussions.
</P>
<P>
It is already apparent that the crisis and its likely effects
are more severe than they initially appeared, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It indicated, however, the global outcome will be a slowdown in
economic growth that will be much less pronounced than the
slowdowns of 1974-75, 1980-83, and 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
In the medium term, global economic growth is still projected
to exceed the average rate seen since 1970, reflecting a continued
strengthening of growth in the countries in transition and
maintenance of the relatively strong performance of the developing
world in the early and mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
The economy of the developing countries is expected to grow 4.1
percent this year and 5.3 percent in 1999 while the figures for
the advanced economies will be 2.4 percent and 2.5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Citing the fact that private foreign financing dries up
together with the large currency depreciations and declines in
asset prices, the report have lowered near-term growth prospects
for Malaysia, the Philippines, and other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Among the advanced economies, the near-term outlook for Japan
has deteriorated further. The world's second largest economy
expects zero growth this year and is projected at about 1.3
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The IMF urges Japan to take further urgent measures in
structural reforms to bring about an early resumption of growth.
</P>
<P>
In North America and western Europe, economic has been well
sustained and appears likely to remain so in the period ahead,
noted the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0024 </DOCNO>
