<HEADLINE> China Emphasizes Management of Underground Water Resources (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xi'an city in northwest China's Shaanxi Province, has recorded
various degrees of subsidence over a 162-sq.km. area, with related
problems directly related to the falling underground.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 percent of China's water supply comes from underground
reserves, with the problems caused by the overuse of underground
water attracting great attention from governments at all levels.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that one of the most effective ways to solve the
problems is to strengthen the management of water resources,
especially underground water resources in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
They suggest recycling water for industrial usage, improving
the quality of surface water and building sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
The development of water-saving industries and agriculture
should be encouraged, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has taken the lead in this respect, said Liu, adding
that the municipality has limited its annual exploitation volume of
underground water to 140 million cu.m., or some 25 percent of
the total available capacity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
