<HEADLINE> Philippine Ruling Party's Presidential Bet Gets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A major Muslim group in the
southern Philippines has decided to support Speaker of the House
of Representatives Jose de Venecia, the presidential candidate of
the ruling Lakas-NUCD party, in the May 11 general elections.
</P>
<P>
In a manifesto published Monday, the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF) said that it endorsed the candidacy of De Venecia
because of his commitment and continuing efforts in bringing peace
to the southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"In the realization of lasting peace and prosperity, we pledge
to support the speaker for his unselfish effort in the
government-MNLF peace agreement," the MNLF said in the manifesto.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto has been submitted to President Fidel Ramos, who
is also chairman of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF and the government signed a permanent peace agreement
in September 1996, ending decades of bloody war between government
troops and MNLF separatists.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Autonomous Region of Muslim Mindanao
was established in 1996 and the MNLF has begun to disarm and
disband its more than 10,000-strong armed force.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF said in the manifesto that the peace treaty is not a
guarantee to lasting peace in Mindanao unless the next president
is committed to pursuing the fulfillment of the deal.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia was trailing far behind opposition candidate Vice
President Joseph Estrada in the presidential race, according to a
March public opinion survey conducted by the Social Weather
Stations, a leading independent pollster in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the poll, Estrada garnered a 28 percent approval rate
against 14 percent for De Venecia, who came in second place in a
tie with former Manila mayor Alfredo Lim of the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
Election analysts said De Venecia's supporting rate could
continue to go up given the ruling party's powerful political
machinery and sufficient campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11 official presidential candidates will run in the
May 11 general elections during which voters will also elect the
vice president, half of the 24-seat Senate members and all the 217
representatives of the lower house. 
</P>
</TEXT>
