<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Monday insisted his nomination of Sergei Kiriyenko for prime
minister would stand despite last week's defeat in the State Duma
(lower house of the parliament).
</P>
<P>
"I will insist on the nomination to the end and I am going to
work constructively (with deputies) given their constructive
work. I don't want political instability in Russia," said the
president before a meeting with Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also said that there was no mention of dissolving the
Duma.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the Duma rejects president's
nominee three times, it is dissolved and new elections are held.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed hope that Kiriyenko will win the second
round vote in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
He said he was satisfied with the fact that Our Home is Russia
faction led by Alexander Shokhin voted favorably in the first
round, saying there may be more votes from other factions.
</P>
<P>
"I will not have to ponder on further steps," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Duma failed to approve Kiriyenko as prime minister in the
first round vote last Friday and soon after Yeltsin nominated him
again for the second round vote, the date of which has not been
fixed. 
</P>
