<HEADLINE> Beijing Starts Large-Scale Spindle Cutting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's largest steel and iron
company today melted 10,000 spindles, symbolizing the large-scale
endeavor to reform its crumbling textile businesses.
</P>
<P>
The melted 10,000 spindles, with the weight of 108 tons, came
from the 25 dismantled spinning machines in Beijing No. 3 Cotton
Mill, a move for Beijing to quickly respond to the call by Premier
Zhu Rongji for a breakthrough in state enterprise reform through
streamlining the country's textile businesses, a section of
industry backbone for decades.
</P>
<P>
"We tried hard to avoid redundant construction at a low level
by strictly limiting the total number of spindles," said Liu
Bingdi, a senior engineer from Beijing Textile Holding Group.
</P>
<P>
A leading textile producer, Beijing has redundant production
capacity in recent years. Many state-owned textile businesses are
in a management and financial abyss against the backdrop of the
market economy.
</P>
<P>
China is determined to greatly reduce current spindles this
year, with 700,000 ones being melted till now. Beijing will reduce
100,000 spindles this year, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
