<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Submits the START-2 Protocol to Duma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Monday resubmitted the START II nuclear weapons protocol for
ratification by the State Duma (lower house of the parliament),
the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, which was signed in New York on September 26,
1997, is an inseparable part of START II treaty signed by Yeltsin
and U.S. President Bill Clinton in 1993.
</P>
<P>
It was submitted to the Duma for ratification on June 20, 1995,
but the Duma has so far refused to approve it.
</P>
<P>
The protocol provides a five-year prolongation of the
limitation of strategic offensive weapons till the end of 2007,
the report quoted a presidential press service as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the START II treaty, the two countries should cut half of
their strategic nuclear arsenals by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ratified the treaty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is likely that the Russian parliament will ratify the treaty
in the first half of this year, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
