<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Kazakstan,
Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia have proposed democratic reforms
for the executive body of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS).
</P>
<P>
Russian Acting Deputy Prime Minister Ivan Rybkin said the four
presidents proposed the changes at a meeting with him recently.
</P>
<P>
Calling the CIS Executive Secretariat "bureaucratic,"
Rybkin, who is responsible for the CIS affairs, said leaders of
the executive body should have the necessary qualities to deal
with the domestic circumstances of CIS members.
</P>
<P>
Up to 2,500 officials of all levels serve in 64 CIS
organizations, most of them since its establishment in December
1991 when the former Soviet Union disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
The four presidents also showed their readiness to attend the
Moscow Meeting of CIS Heads of State to be held on April 29, said
the acting deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The 12 CIS members are Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Georgia,
Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan,
Ukraine and Uzbekistan. 
