<HEADLINE> 40 Percent of Ethiopian Roads Need Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Roads
Authority said on Monday that 40 percent of roads in the country
need to be rehabilitated, reported the Ethiopian News Agency
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 23,810-kilometer-long roads in the country, only
20 percent is in good condition with 40 percent damaged due to
lack of renovations, the report quoted Zaid Wolde-Gebriel,
Manager of Planning and Program Department of the authority as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Wolde-Gebriel said that the main problems facing the road
sector in Ethiopia are the shortage of highways and the
deteriorating conditions of the existing ones.
</P>
<P>
According to the manager, only 3,656 kilometers of the
highways across the country are asphalt roads, of which more than
half are in bad shape.
</P>
<P>
Less than 50 percent of the 12,113 kilometers of the gravel
roads in the country are said to be in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
Wolde-Gebriel said the the deteriorating quality of the roads
is partly the result of the scanty budget which was allotted by
the previous regime.
</P>
<P>
The recently established road fund has given due attention to
renovating the existing roads along with the construction of new
ones, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
