<HEADLINE> Art Auction Closes in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An two-day art auction which ended
today in Xiamen city, in east China's Fujian Province, has
auctioned off 43 percent of the 500 works of art and other items,
at a total price of 1.76 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The percentages of traditional Chinese paintings, porcelain
pieces, and jade items auctioned off stands at 48 percent, 31
percent and 50 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jing, deputy general manager of the Beijing-based Kangrong
Auction Ltd. said that the auction result is not satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
He said that although many people have discriminating taste in
the art works on display, they prefer to clinch the deal privately
instead of by competitive means.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributes the phenomenon to the fact that Xiamen is a
medium-sized city and its residents are not willing to show off
their wealth, which is in sharp contrast to Beijingners.
</P>
<P>
The auction, jointly sponsored by the Hengsheng Auction Company
in Xiamen and the Kangrong Auction Ltd. in Beijing, offers such
works of art as traditional Chinese paintings, porcelain pieces,
jade, diamond jewelry and rare French wines.
</P>
<P>
The most expensive item auctioned off is a copper stove, which
is as big as a fist and made in the early period of the Qing
Dynasty(1644-1911). It was bought by a Hong Kong businessman at a
price of 18,000 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
