KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Defense Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said Monday that the armed forces of Malaysia
and Brunei would continue combined operations to fight forest
fires in Sarawak, east Malaysia, which have caused lingering haze
over Brunei.
</P>
<P>
"Brunei has despatched two air force helicopters to help the
authorities in Sarawak put out the forest fires," he said after
meeting Royal Brunei Armed Forces Chief Major General Pengiran
Pahlawan Haji Abidin Pengiran Ahmad here.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said the Royal Malaysian Air Force have in turn
deployed two C-130 Hercules aircraft for cloud-seeding sorties as
one way to douse the fires.
</P>
<P>
Forest fires in Lambir near Miri in the state have reportedly
engulfed a two-kilometer stretch of peat soil area along the
Miri-Bintulu road, causing thick smoke screens over Miri and the
neighboring oil-rich sultanate.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said that besides collaboration in
operations, the two armed forces also cooperated in training and
intelligence sharing.
</P>
<P>
He said Brunei has sought to share Malaysia's expertise and
experience in handling frigates as the sultanate's navy would take
delivery of such vessels soon.
</P>
<P>
Pahlawan Haji Abidin, who arrived here earlier in the day, also
called on his Malaysian counterpart General Ismail Omar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
