<HEADLINE> Large Buddhist Resort Open to Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A Buddhist culture center in
tropical Hainan Province, the largest of its kind in China, opened
to tourists today.
</P>
<P>
The center is situated in the Nanshan Culture Tourism Zone
which is 40 km to the west of Sanya City.
</P>
<P>
Being a key tourism project in Hainan, the zone is expected to
cover 35 sq km on land and scores of sq km of water surface,
featuring Chinese folk culture, tropical sights, ecological
protection and Buddhist and Taoist cultures.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to need a total investment of six
billion yuan (about 723 million US dollars) and will be completed
in eight years.
</P>
<P>
As the first stage of the entire project, the Buddhist culture
center began construction in November, 1995, and 210 million yuan
has been spent, with major buildings highlighting the style of
prosperous Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
Inside the center, a grand religious fair was held yesterday
morning in front of the newly-built Precious Hall of the Great
Hero in Nanshan Temple. More than 1,000 people, including central
and local officials and hundreds of monks were present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
