<HEADLINE> Purchase of Stocks Down, Bond Investment Up in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in South Korean
firms plunged by 74 percent in March to 561.9 billion won (401
million U.S. dollars) as against 2.2 trillion won (1.5 billion
dollars) in February, said the Financial Supervisory Commission on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign purchase of bonds surged by 114 percent to
one trillion won (714 million dollars) in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The securities authorities attributed the change to the recent
appreciation of won against dollar.
</P>
<P>
The won's value against the dollar has hovered at 1,300-1,400
for more than three weeks, prompting more overseas investors to
dump their shareholdings for profitable bonds.
</P>
<P>
The rate had slumped to the 1,600-level at the end of last year
when the country began to suffer a serious financial crisis
triggered by corporate collapses and bad loans by financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Leading investors in the South Korean stock market are
foreigners such as Americans and Europeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
