<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in Spain Hits Record Low in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Spain fell to an
18-year low in March with 2.039 million people out of work,
according to statistics released Monday by the Spanish Labor
Department.
</P>
<P>
In March, the number of jobless accounted for 12.58 percent of
Spain's total labor force, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to government efforts to increase employment, the past
two years have seen steady reduction in the number of the jobless.
</P>
<P>
In the three months to February, the number of unemployed fell
by 77,700, while and 28,700 people found new jobs in March.
</P>
<P>
Also in March, about 937,770 people signed work contracts with
their companies, 90.16 percent of which were long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decrease, unemployment in Spain is still considered
higher than that of other European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government is reportedly working hard to bring
about "a new employment program" to ease the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
