<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Hopes to Solve POWs Issue with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday expressed hope to
solve the issue of prisoners of war (POWs) with Iraq on the 10th
anniversary of the end of Iran-Iraq war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
According to Tehran radio, head of Iran's commission on the
POWs affairs Abdollah Najafi said at a press conference that if
Iran and Iraq continue to swap POWs, the issue left over from the
Iran-Iraq war can be solved during the current Iranian year
(starting on March 21).
</P>
<P>
He said that officials from the two countries would hold
discussion on the border in the near future and a final talk
would be held in Baghdad to release all POWs.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Baghdad started a new round of release of POWs on
April 4. Najafi said that under the agreements reached between
Iran and Iraq following the eighth Islamic summit held in Tehran
last December, 5,584 Iraqi POWs were swapped for 319 Iranians
during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said that seven Iraqi POWs announced their willingness to
stay in Iran while another died of heart attack when he was handed
over to the officials of the International Red Cross Society.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that more than 39,000 Iranian POWs
were exchanged with 54,000 Iraqis since the two countries began
the exchange of POWs in 1990. But he noted that although the
majority of the registered POWs have been released, there were
documents indicating that a number of Iranian POWs are still kept
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the problem of those missing in
action (MIA) would also be solved through cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Following the visit by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf to Tehran in January, the two countries reached an
agreement to form a joint committee to follow up the POWs issue in
order to remove the obstacles for normalization of bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Auto Investment Mission to Visit Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A major U.S. automotive investment
mission will visit Manila from Wednesday to Friday to explore
possibilities for further investment in the Philippine market, the
Philippine News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The mission was sponsored by the American Chamber of Commerce,
the Motor Equipment Manufacturers Association (MEMA) and the U.S.
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Business Council.
</P>
<P>
With the inclusion of the automotive manufacturing sector in
the Philippines' 1998 Investment Priorities Plan and the decision
by Ford Motor Company to invest in the country, the interest of
other major U.S. manufacturers in investing in the Philippines has
increased.
</P>
<P>
The mission includes representatives of Ford, General Motors
and Chrysler as well as those from Lear Corporation, United
Technologies, Dana Asia-Pacific, Johnson Controls, Visteon
Automotive Systems and other automotive manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
During their visit, the mission will meet with Philippine
Secretary of Trade and Industry Cesar Bautista and other senior
government officials.
</P>
<P>
A major objective of the mission is to explore the possibility
of U.S.-Philippine auto components joint ventures and
partnerships.  
</P>
