<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Open Three More Airports to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will soon to open three
more airports to international flights, local newspaper Noticias
Monday quoted a senior Mozambican officical as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Industry, Trade and Tourism Mohomed Rafique
told Noticias newspaper that three more airports, namely Tete,
Lichinga and Ponta de Ouro, will soon open to the international
transports.
</P>
<P>
The three airports are located respectively in the northern
provinces of Tete and Niassa and the southern Maputo Province.
</P>
<P>
Rafique made the announcement last week at the opening
ceremony of the Pemba Airport, which is the capital of the
northern Cabo Delgado Province bordering Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy minister, the construction of runways,
control towers and additional lounges are in full swing in the
three airports.
</P>
<P>
Rafique said that with Pemba Airport opened, South Africans,
Europeans and other tourists from the Middle East now can come to
Cabo Delgado Province directly by air without transits in the
cities of Maputo or Beira.
</P>
<P>
After the Vilankulo Airport in south Mozambique opened in last
April to the international direct flights, large number of
tourist have come from South Africa and Zimbabwe, quadrupling the
population around the airport and the transportation of cargos,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said that the Mozambican government has
increased investment in the infrastructures in the past few years
in order to speed up the economic growth in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are only five international airports in
Mozambique -- Maputo and Vilankulo in the south, Beira in the
center and Nampula and Pemba in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
