<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President Pressures Conglomerates into Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
Monday pressed his financially troubled nation's top five business
groups to speed up self-reforms.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he was not satisfied with the "pace and intensity" of
the five top conglomerates' restructuring programs.
</P>
<P>
"They have to further hasten and strengthen their restructuring
efforts," Kim was quoted as saying by Kang Bong-kyun, his top
policy advisor.
</P>
<P>
Kim's pressure on the five conglomerates comes at a time when
the nation's labor groups threatened to unilaterally abolish an
agreement with employers and the government on sharing the burden
of economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The labor groups accused the conglomerates of failing to honor
their previous pledge of reviving the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
A five-point reform agreement, reached between Kim and the
country's top 30 conglomerates in February, calls for
transparency in business management, an end to the
cross-subsidiary loan payments, the establishment of a healthy
financial structure, support for small firms, and making majority
shareholders and managers take greater responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the top 30 should take serious self-reform
measures, including the appointment of external board members, the
sell-off of real estate and marginal subsidiaries. However, they
have made little progress.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the top 30 conglomerates were blamed for devouring
banks loans and shirking responsibility for fostering the
financial woes with their high debt build-up and over-expansion.
</P>
<P>
"The president believes that the conglomerates should push for
more intense reform programs if we are to win the people's
cooperation for overcoming the economic crisis," Kang said.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerates should sell what they have to sell and merge
what they have to merge, added the president's advisor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
