<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister, US Under Secretary of Commerce Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Issues related to trade
imbalances should be solved through development, rather than by
resorting to the use of restrictions or other negative measures,
Shi Guangsheng, Chinese minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
cooperation, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Shi made the remarks during a meeting with U.S. Commerce
Department Under Secretary of International Trade David Aaron.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China attaches great importance to developing
Sino-U.S. commercial ties which have played an important role in
bilateral relations and offer vast potential in wide-ranging areas.
</P>
<P>
Shi pointed to imbalances in Sino-U.S. trade and noted that
China has consistently adhered to the principle of balanced
imports and exports. He said China holds that balanced trade
should be achieved through development, rather than by the
introduction of restrictions or other negative measures.
</P>
<P>
Aaron outlined U.S. interest in joining efforts with China in
the fields of aviation, housing, energy, environmental protection
and infrastructure, and expressed the hope to enhance
communications between business people of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Aaron noted that his visit coincides with preparations for
President Clinton to visit China in June.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Secretary Madeleine Albright and U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky are scheduled to visit China on
the heels of recent visits by Under State Secretaries John Holum
and Thomas Pickering.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his meeting with Shi, Aaron joined Chinese
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Sun Zhenyu
to cochair the 11th meeting of the Sino-U.S. Joint Commission on
Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has outlined regular midterm negotiation mechanisms
of the current commission.
</P>
<P>
Shi noted the great significance of holding such a meeting on
the eve of President Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation, led by Aaron, includes representatives of
17 major American companies from wide-ranging areas, including
seven insurance companies and other companies from the
construction, information technology and transportation sectors.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs statistics show that the trade volume between
China and the United States hit 6.98 billion U.S. dollars for
first two months of the year, up 20.5 on the 1997 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
