<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Uganda's Teachers Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom has provided
seven billion Ugandan Shillings (some 64 million U.S. Dollars)
for the In-Service Secondary Teacher Education Project (INSSTEP)
in Uganda, the New Vision reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Dave Fish, the head of the British
Department of International Development in Eastern Africa, as
saying that the funds are to be used to train headmasters,
teachers, school inspectors and training center coordinators in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The fund will facilitate 25 training centers in the country
under the joint Ugandan-British project INSSTEP.
</P>
<P>
Dave Fish predicted that the demand for secondary school
teachers will expand in the future in the wake of the
implementation of Universal Program of Education (UPE) program in
Uganda and that the INSSTEP project will provide opportunities
for the teachers in further improvement in their professionals
skills.
</P>
<P>
The UPE program provides free primary education to four
children for every family.
</P>
<P>
Dave Fish said that the training centers will be successful
only if teachers recognize the value of raising the level of
their professional skills. The training centers receive direct
support from schools and local administrations, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
