<HEADLINE> Africa's Growth Depends on GDP: ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) has called on African countries to increase
their national domestic product (GDP) to avoid continued
marginalization from the global economy.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest ILO report, sub-Saharan Africa, long
beset by economic adversity and civil disorder, is showing the
first signs of economic resurgence, This Day newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
It disclosed that while recovery prospects can be further
boosted by domestic reforms and increased international
investment, acclerated job and income growth are now critical to
sustaining the upturn and maintaining political stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The report, an outcome of ILO and United Nations Development
Program for Africa tagged "Jobs for Africa", also indicated that
while economic performance of most sub-Saharan African countries
has been far from satisfactory for the last two decades, the
outcome has not been uniformly bad.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, five of the stronger performers in
the region, including Equatorial Guinea, Lesotho and Uganda,
enjoyed average GDP growth rates of seven percent or more during
1992-95 period.
</P>
<P>
During the four-year period, five other countries grew by an
average of 4-5 percent with eight others growing by roughtly 3-4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that eight sub-Saharan African
countries, including Cameroon, Angola, Sierra Leone, Rwanda and
Zambia, experienced real declines during the perod.
</P>
<P>
One of the reasons for the envisaged turnaround in countries
which showed an average growth is the increase in domestic
investment which the report showed an average increase of over 10
percent in eight countries.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is the rising level of foreign investment,
which "while tiny by international comparisons, nonetheless grew
by more than 100 percent in 10 countries".
</P>
<P>
Other reasons are stronger prices for raw materials and
agriculture products, icnreased European demand for African
manufactured goods, expanding African enterpreurship, rising
labor productivity and heightened international commitment to
African development.
</P>
<P>
However, the report stressed that the main emphasis of policy
makers today "should be encouraging new, private sector
enterprises, particularly those which are small in scale and
labor intensive, and on enabling small enterprises to expand,
innovate and penetrate new markets, including export markets."
</P>
<P>
The ILO report also calls for a reduction of the external debt
of the 29 severely indebted low income countries in Africa as
"currently, debt service accounts for about four percent of GDP
in the region".
</P>
<P>
The debt figure should be cut by half to free up resources for
future productive investment, ILO suggested.  
</P>
</TEXT>
