<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Raise price of Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The price of water for industry
and hydro-electric power stations will go up considerably this
year and slightly for agricultural use.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission says that waterworks
need to increase water fees in 1998 to reduce losses and improve
profit, and that China will set the rates for urban areas.
</P>
<P>
To improve efficiency, the country is encouraging people to
save water resources. Any companies that waste water will be
fined, and urban residents and companies will pay higher prices
for going beyond their quotas.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the price of 1,000 tons of Yellow River water was
equal to that of a bottle of mineral water. Farmers are being
encouraged to use modern irrigation technology.
</P>
<P>
China should treat water as a kind of commodity and set a
reasonable price, according to Jiang Chunyun, vice-Chairman of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Niu Maosheng, Minister of Water Resources, said that China will
develop favorable policies encouraging people to save water and
new projects that do not take water-saving into consideration will
not be approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
