<HEADLINE> Two Forest Fires Getting Stronger in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Two newly-detected forest fires in
the Philippines were getting stronger, a senior government
official said Monday in a report to the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Fortunato Dejoras, an executive officer of the National
Disaster Coordinating Council, said in the report that the fire in
Bokod, Benguet province, the northern Philippines, has damaged
some 25,00 hectares of forest areas.
</P>
<P>
He said fire fighters and civilian volunteers were constructing
firebreaks to contain the fire and the Armed Forces of the
Philippines has been asked to use water bombs to extinguish the
fire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the forest fire starting on April 9 in two villages
near Iligan city, the southern Philippines, has forced five
families to evacuate to safer places and burned down eight houses,
he added.
</P>
<P>
One platoon of the Philippine Army's 60th Infantry Battalion
has been dispatched to the said villages to assist in
fire-fighting operations while 40 personnel from different
government departments were working hard to contain the fire,
Dejoras said.
</P>
<P>
The two fires were the latest found in the country. Since March
this year a number of forest fires have gripped the southern part
of the country, killing at least three people and damaging
thousands of hectares of forest land.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government announced earlier that the forest
fires in the south had been under control. 
</P>
