<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Calls for Long Millennium Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England has said that a
three-day Millennium Holiday, at the end of next year, will help
overcome problems posed by the millennium computer bug.
</P>
<P>
With fears growing about the consequences of year 2000
computer crashes, it is understood that people who think they will
be celebrating the new millennium on holiday will, in fact, be
working flat out, trying to deal with the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
Don Cruickshand, chairman of the Action 2000 campaign, told a
British paper, the Independent, that the consequences of
chain-link "crashes" between computers are completely unknown.
</P>
<P>
The scale of the risks involved was underlined by a report
released recently saying that foreign exchange settlement failures
could quadruple in the first week of January 2000, costing the
markets as much as 10 billion U.S. dollars in one week.
</P>
<P>
The impending crisis is threatened by the fact that many
computers have not been programmed to distinguish between 2000 and
1900 when their two-digit dates change to 00 from the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, warned: "We face
a day of judgement on that first day of the year 2000. The IT
systems on which the entire business community now depends are not
capable of recognizing or responding predictably to dates beyond
the end of this century."
</P>
<P>
The bank said the continuation of orderly markets might not be
possible "if a large enough proportion of the participants are
unable to trade or settle - and particularly if those still
operating try to make a profit out of the situation."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the exchanges will be planning how to manage such a
crisis, including procedures for closing the market altogether,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
At the request of British Prime Minister Tony Blair, the G8
nations are reported to discuss the global implications of the
millennium bug at the next summit to be held in Birmingham next
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
