<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, France Sign MOU on Industrial,  Technological Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and France Monday
signed here a memorandum of understanding (M0U) to promote their
industrial and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed here between the Malaysian Industrial
Development Authority (MIDA) and the Agency for the International
Development of French Technology and Trade (CFME-ACTIM), in the
presence of International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz
and French Minister of State in charge of Foreign Trade Jacques
Dondoux.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation under the MOU would be especially in priority
sectors such as telecommunications, multimedia, transport
equipment, machinery and bio-technologies.
</P>
<P>
Dondoux told reporters after the signing that France will not
revise its investments in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"We will not revise our investments in Malaysia. We believe
Malaysia will overcome the economic crisis, and I urge French
firms to continue to invest in Malaysia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The French delegation is scheduled to discuss with MIDA
joint-venture possibilities in telecommunications and multimedia.
</P>
<P>
"We already have investments in telecommunications by companies
like Alcatel here. Now we are discussing opportunities in
multimedia," Dondoux said.
</P>
<P>
Other French companies with manufacturing operations in
Malaysia include Fichet Bauche, Mafipro MAPA Group of Companies,
Jourbert, Michelin, Peugeot and Montagut.
</P>
<P>
As at the end of 1997, there were 253 French companies
operating in Malaysia, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
There is potential for France to further invest in the capital
and high-technology industries such as the production of machine
tools, heavy equipment, automotive equipment and in the
resource-based and petro- chemical industries, according to MIDA.
</P>
<P>
France is the fourth largest investor in Malaysia from the
European Union after Germany, the United Kingdom and the
Netherlands. Two French projects worth 4.2 million ringgit (1.166
million U.S. dollars) have been approved for this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Rafidah, MIDA approved 33 French projects with
capital investments of 4.3 billion ringgit (1.194 million U.S.
dollars) between 1990 and 1997 mainly in the production of rubber
products, non-metallic mineral products, textiles, electronics,
plastics, petroleum and coal, and food manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
