<HEADLINE> Mitchell Warns N.Irish Peace Agreement in Danger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's new assembly
could collapse in acrimony within 18 months, talks chairman George
Mitchell warned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody can rule out the possibility that 18 months from now,
they can't get the assembly to work, that the whole process simply
stops," the former U.S. senator told the Times newspaper in London
before flying to New York.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell, the broker who helped clinch Friday's historic peace
accord, hoped that the parties concerned would begin to develop a
"sense of accomplishment and mutual endeavor" by cooperating in
the assembly.
</P>
<P>
"It will take a real effort to make this work," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell said his biggest concern was that there remained a
complete lack of trust between the feuding Unionists and
Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
 He also warned that extremists on both sides of the sectarian
divide could step up attacks in the weeks leading up to May 22
referendums being held on Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
The major political parties in Northern Ireland reached a
peace agreement last Friday, formally ending the three-decade
bloody conflict in the divided province during which more than
3,000 people were killed. 
</P>
