<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebels Attack Gendarme Station in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) has attacked a gendarme station in eastern
province of Tunceli, local newspaper Milliyet reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Three PKK militants robbed a taxi car and raided the Cicekli
Gendarme Station in the region from the taxi on Sunday night,
wounding one non-commissioned officer and two soldiers on duty,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the three PKK rebels fleed to a forest in the
area following their attack.
</P>
<P>
The wounded officer, who was in serious conditions, was taken
to a hospital in Elazig province by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been creating incidents in various tourist regions
in Turkey since the start of the tourist season in April.
</P>
<P>
Turkish security forces clashed with the PKK guerrillas in the
tourist province of Antalya along the Mediterranean Sea over the
past three days and 10 PKK rebels were killed in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Emergency Regional Rule Governor Aydin Arslan has said that
25,000 PKK militants have been rendered ineffective since Turkey
imposed the state of emergency in the southeast in 1987 in a bid
to wipe out PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels, who have sought shelters in norther Iraq
since the 1991 Gulf War, often launch cross-border attacks on
Turkey's military and civilian targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
