<HEADLINE> Israel to Discuss Military Accord With Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu will pay a visit to Poland next week, during which he
will discuss the implementation of a deal on bilateral military
cooperation, local daily Haaretz reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deal, under which Israel Aircraft Industries (IAI) will
upgrade Hussar helicopters for the Polish Army, is the largest of
its kind entered into by Poland since the collapse of the Soviet
bloc and is worth 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some of the upgraded helicopters are earmarked for the Polish
army and the rest for export.
</P>
<P>
The report said that during the visit, Netanyahu will discuss
this issue with Polish leaders to urge Poland to implement the
deal.
</P>
<P>
Senior Israeli government sources noted that this is the major
item on the agenda of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum of understanding was initiated on September 6,
1997, and the agreement was signed about a month later in Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed shortly before the elections in
Poland, which led to the formation of the new government headed by
the Solidarity Party. But the party's leadership objects to the
project.
</P>
<P>
Polish Defense Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz has attributed the
delay in implementing the agreement to a new law passed by the
Polish parliament, which forbids the government to sign contracts
with corporations without exhausting certain procedures.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Poland, Netanyahu will take part in the
"March of the Living," the annual ceremony to mark the
Holocaust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
