<HEADLINE> Leprosy Cases Fall in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A multi-drug therapy treatment
and an aggressive public awareness campaign have resulted in the
fall of leprosy cases in Kenya from 10,000-plus a decade ago to
about 700 last year, the East African newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Between 350-400 active cases of the debilitating disease are
being picked up annually, the head of the National Tuberculosis
and Leprosy Project (NTLP), Daniel Kibuga, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Health education is a prerequisite. People will know that if
detected early, leprosy is simple to treat and curable," said
Kibuga.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO), which introduced the
multi-drug therapy, says the world is well on the way to
eliminate leprosy as a public health problem before the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy is caused by a bacterium, called Mycobacterium leprae,
which produced very slowly and mainly affects skin, nerves
and mucous membrane. If untreated, there can be progressive and
permanent damage to skin, limbs and eyes.
</P>
<P>
"But visible symptoms may not show themselves for six, or even
10 years," says John Mansoer, a technical advisor to NTLP.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy has been dreaded through the centuries and was for
long universally considered incurable. In 1940, the first drug to
be developed, dapsone, cured the disease, but only if the patient
regularly took the correct dose over many years.
</P>
<P>
The leprosy bacterium later developed resistance to dapsone,
leading to the adoption of cocktail of three drugs -- dapsone,
rifamici and clofazimine -- by WHO in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Strategy has been adopted by all endemic countries during
the past fiver years, and the resulting progress in the control
of leprosy has been remarkable.
</P>
<P>
The number of registered leprosy cases fell significantly for
the first time in the 1980s, from 5.4 million in 1985 to 3.7
million in 1990, representing a decrease of 31.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Though a person may be completely cured, Kibuga said, severe
damage to limbs usually can not always be put right leading to a
long time problem of rehabilitation or treatment for people
disabled by the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to NTLP, up to 40 percent of cases are in advanced
stages of the disease because patients don't seek treatment
early enough, or doctors take inordinately long to identify the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Human beings seem to be the only natural host of the leprosy
bacterium, which medics experts suspect, is transmitted mainly
from the nasal discharge of infected people, but might also be
passed on by skin contact.
</P>
<P>
A total of 79 countries are technically endemic for leprosy
today. Of these, only 25 are rated as the "most endemic"
countries as they contribute to 93 percent of all cases.
</P>
<P>
Among the 25 nations are Bangladesh, Brazil, Cambodia, Chad,
Columbia, Egypt, Ethiopia, Guinea, India, Indonesia, Iran,
Madagascar, Mali, Mexico, Mozambique, Nepal, Niger, Nigeria,
Philippines, Sudan, Thailand and Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
