<HEADLINE> AL Urges PNA, Hamas to End Verbal Warfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has urged the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) to halt their war of words, saying it only
benefits Israel, the Egyptian Gazette reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Israel is the primary beneficiary of this verbal war between
the Palestinian National Authority and Hamas," AL Assistant
Secretary General for Palestine Affairs Said Kamal told reporters
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League is asking the two Palestinian parties to show
restraint and use the language of patriotic unity," he was quoted
by the English daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kamal also urged both sides to suspend their differences and
concentrate on the main points of disagreement between the
Palestinian people, led by the Palestine Liberation Organization,
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The PNA and Hamas have blamed each other for the murder of
chief Hamas bomb maker Muhi Sharif, whose charred body was found
on March 29 in a car blown up in the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Palestinian version, the explosion
was staged to cover up the murder by rival Hamas members.
</P>
<P>
But Hamas, which opposes the Israeli-Palestinian peace accords,
has denied a hand in the murder and accused Israel and the PNA of
collaborating in killing Sharif.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Palestinian chief delegate to the Arab League
Mohammad Sobeih warned against the consequences of the absence of
direct contact between Hamas and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
"There are many parties who would like to make use of this
situation...Direct contact is necessary to deny any chance to
misuse the assassination," he told Egypt's Middle East News
Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
