<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Turkey Needs Aircraft Carriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey would soon become one of
the few countries that possess aircraft carriers to safeguard its
interests as a regional power, naval officials said.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Daily News Monday quoted officials from
the Naval Forces Command as saying that "The notion of Turkish
aircraft carriers crisscrossing the waters of the western
Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Black Sea in the 2000s is not a
fantasy but a necessity."
</P>
<P>
The officials stressed that Turkey's national might, geography
and historical factors "are forcing Turkey to become a regional
power whose interests are not limited to its neighbors only,"
adding that this can only be achieved with the formation of a
powerful flotilla, including aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
They said the navy's operational capabilities should be
extended beyond the Turkish shores to all areas within Turkey's
interests.
</P>
<P>
"The significant participation of the Turkish troops in the
United Nations peace-keeping operations in Somalia, Bosnia and
Albania shows the world that Turkey has become a regional force
whose interests are not limited to its neighbors," the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain, France, Russia, India, Italy,
Spain and Thailand are the countries comprising the so-called
"aircraft-carrier-countries club."
</P>
<P>
The United States has 12 aircraft carriers, Britain three,
France, Russia and India two each, while Italy, Spain and Thailand
one each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Opposition Calls for Inter-Party Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's National Lima Party has
called for resumption of inter-party dialogue which was suspended
last December, Times of Zambia reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted president of the party, Ben Kapita, as
saying at the weekend that the dialogue should be held urgently
and political parties that are not ready to participate should be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party dialogue was suspended after former President
Kenneth Kaunda was arrested last December in alleged involvement
in the October 28 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Ben Kapita said that with the state of emergency imposed after
the foiled coup lifted last month, political parties should hold
a meeting to resolve their differences and concentrate on
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
He said that politicians will lose their relevance to the
public if they continue to procrastinate on dialogue because
people are more concerned with issues which affect their daily
lives.
</P>
<P>
"We, as politicians, must meet and resolve whatever
differences we have," said Kapita, "People expect us to resolve
our political differences and start dealing with economic issues,
otherwise, we are going to lose the confidence of the Zambian
people."
</P>
<P>
Kapita said that he has consulted 10 parties including the
United National Independence Party (UNIP) led by Kaunda and
Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC), and all of them have indicated
their willingness to take part in the talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Kapita accused the ruling party of not being serious
in dialogue and said that efforts made to hold dialogue have been
frustrated by it.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary inter-party talks held in early December last year
decided to hold a inter-party summit early January this year.
However, the summit failed to materialize because many parties
quitted the dialog in protest against the arrest of Kaunda.
</P>
</TEXT>
