<HEADLINE> Huge Investment Needed for Nigeria's Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Electric Power
Authority (NEPA) has called on the government to provide fund totaling
5.5 billion U.S. Dollars to effect repairs
of its four thermal power plants.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of comprehensive overhaul of the aged plants make them
susceptible to frequent breakdowns which constitute severe constraints
to effect generation, scheduling," NEPA said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned corporation is said to be generating electricity at
68 percent below its capacity of 5,958 mw, with an output of 1,925 mw,
compared with the national peak demand of 2,446 mw.
</P>
<P>
According to NEPA, four major plants with a combined generating
capacity of 3,440 mw, need urgent repairs.
</P>
<P>
Under this year's budget, the government earmarked three billion
naira (about 37 million dollars) to rehabilitate power plants.
</P>
<P>
However, in its first official reaction to the 1998 budgetary
provision, NEPA management described the amout as only "a tip of the
iceberg".
</P>
<P>
But Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani said the government could
not provide such funds demanded by NEPA, saying "when private
investment come in, they will put things right."
</P>
<P>
According to a government program, preparations will be made
this year to offer the state-monopolized electricity sector for
privatization, which the government wishes to boost capacity and
provide adequate power supply in the country.  
</P>
