<HEADLINE> Korean Talks Reconvene in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The vice-ministerial-level talks
between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the
Republic of Korea (ROK) reopened in Beijing this afternoon, after
a morning session was cancelled.
</P>
<P>
This closed-door working level session, instead of a plenum,
started at 15:00 pm, with the head delegates and one delegate from
each side attending.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which started in Beijing Saturday afternoon, are the
first government contact between the two in nearly four years. The
issues to be discussed include food supplies and fertilizer from
the South, the reunion of families separated since the 1950s,
special envoy exchanges, and the North-South Basic Agreement.
</P>
<P>
After talks on Saturday and Sunday, both negotiators have
expressed guarded optimism over the ongoing talks.
</P>
<P>
However, an official from the ROK embassy said he did not know
what progress negotiators made, nor how long the talks would
last. "A statement might be signed as a result of the talks," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK embassy in Beijing did not respond to telephone queries
for comment.
</P>
<P>
Chun Kum Chul, a member of the Administration Council, is
heading a five-member DPRK delegation, and Jeong Se Hyun,
vice-minister of the National Unification, is leading an equal
number on the ROK side.
</P>
<P>
The first-round plenum on Saturday afternoon was said to have
been conducted "in an open and friendly way", and the second
round, on Sunday morning, "in a good atmosphere", following a
working level session in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This landmark Beijing talks follow an inconclusive second round
of Four-Party Korean peace talks, which ended in Geneva on March
21 after six days.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of journalists from the ROK, Japan and other nations are
closely watching the development of the talks at a five-star hotel
in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK proposed that Beijing be the venue for the
talks. China is the only country that has formal diplomatic ties
with all three political powers involved in the Korean Peninsula:
the DPRK, the ROK, and the U.S.  
</P>
</TEXT>
