<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia to take Measures to Prevent Hajj </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia is considering
ways to prevent future repetition of last week's stampede and
other tragedies that have marked the annual pilgrimage in recent
years, reports reaching here from Saudi Arabia said Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people died when a stampede took place Thursday
on an 80 meter-wide bridge on Mina plain, 10 kilometers from Saudi
holy city of Mecca, during the last day performance of this year's
Hajj season. The official Saudi Press Agency put the death toll at
118.
</P>
<P>
A senior Saudi official, whose name was not given, was quoted
as saying that Saudi authorities have set up a committee to study
ways of easing congestion on certain pilgrimage sites.
</P>
<P>
He said that some of the proposals the Saudi government is
looking into are to widen the bridge and allow people on it
only every 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was the scene of a similar stampede in 1994 that
killed some 270 pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the burial of the stampede victims this year, reports
said burial in Mecca is the preferred option of the families of
the deceased. Some of the burials have already taken place and
some will take place over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, pilgrims from other countries have started leaving
Saudi Arabia for home and the process is expected to last for a
month to complete.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia receives more than 2 million Muslim pilgrims
every year from various parts of the world and many departments
of the Saudi government make intricate preparations throughout
the year for the world's biggest gathering of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
So far Saudi Arabia has spent billions of U.S. dollars in
improving serving and other facilities for the annual gathering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
