<HEADLINE> China And U.S. Cooperate in Teaching Teenagers About Puberty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Education and
the U.S.'s Procter &AMP; Gamble (P&AMP;G) began a ten-year program today
to help teenage schoolgirls in China deal with puberty.
</P>
<P>
P&AMP;G will donate 7 million yuan (about 850,000 US dollars) to
the National School Health Education Development Fund for the
program. Its CEO John Pepper gave the Education Ministry an
initial one million yuan at a ceremony here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Song Jinxian, the ministry's physical, health, and art
education director, said at the ceremony that education about
puberty is a part of Chinese general education, and because it
concerns their health, it should be addressed by schools, parents,
and society as a whole, and that foreign experience can be used
for better results.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that cooperation between education
departments and social organizations is an effective way to
develop education.
</P>
<P>
P&AMP;G conducted trial programs in cities of Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Wuhan, and Chengdu in the latter half of last year,
which were judged a success.
</P>
<P>
Jing Yidan, a news anchorwoman at China Central Television,
said that, as the mother of a teenage girl, she feels the program
is significant because it is long-term and nationwide, meaning
that even girls living in remote areas can eventually benefit from
it.
</P>
<P>
P&AMP;G, one of the world's largest consumer goods producers, has
11 joint ventures in China. It first came to China in 1988, and
its investment in China exceeds 300 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
