<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Decides to Cut Govt Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
decided to cut its expenditure by 20 percent to ease the
diteriorating fiscal situation facing the country, the East
African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures announced last week are the retrenchment of
civil servants, a proposed pay freeze and a 20 percent cut in the
government's wage.
</P>
<P>
Facing the deteriorating fiscal situation, the Kenyan
government has decided to cut its expenditure as a major step
towards mending relations with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) which halted its aid package to the country in the mid of
last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The east African state expects to raise some 12.6 billion
Shillings (210 million U.S. Dollars) through the cut in the
government wage bill and 7.4 billion Shillings (126.6 million
Dollars) from other savings in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The total sum of the money saved, which will be used to redeem
the domestic debt, will achieve a budget surplus of three percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP) per year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae said that the measures,
which will be tabled in parliament as part of the new budget in
June, were a prerequisite for initiating discussions with the IMF
under the existing Enhanced Structural Adjustment Fund (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The report said the proposed retrenchment in the public
service, which is expected to be controversial, has received the
backing of Britain, among other bilateral and multilateral
donors.
</P>
<P>
A member of the donor community suggested that Kenya could
follow the practice adopted by other countries where those
retrenched have either worked continuously for 30 years, or have
attained 50 or 55 years of age or both.
</P>
<P>
Kenya fell out with the IMF in July over issues of good
governance and what the Fund saw as the government's reluctance
to crackdown on corruption. Following the standoff, Kenya lost
205 million U.S. Dollars in aid.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's debt has increased from 110 billion Shillings (1.8
billion U.S. Dollars) in 1996 to some 140 billion Shillings (2.3
billion U.S. Dollars) in January 1998, and is expected to rise to
150 billion Shillings (2.5 billion U.S. Dollars) in the next
three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
