<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Rebuffs Reports About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines Monday rebuffed allegations that no one is allowed to
bring more than 10,000 U.S. dollars out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said that anyone can buy
the greenback more than this amount from any accredited banks and
money exchange shops and take them out of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the banks are given the option to
decide whether to sell dollars provided that the transactions will
be covered by proper documents.
</P>
<P>
Singson's reaction came after reports that the Central Bank has
approved a 150 percent reduction in the amount of dollars one
person can take out of the country to 10,000 dollars from the
current limit of 25,000.00 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The restriction on dollar outflow was allegedly imposed by the
government as a result of the prevailing currency crisis that hurt
most of the economies in the region, including the Philippines, so
that capital flights can be minimized.
</P>
<P>
While the country needs dollars to sustain its import
requirements, the private sector is urging the government to take
monetary measures to regulate the outflow of dollars from the
country. 
</P>
