<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Uganda Seeking to Enter World Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan and Ugandan delegates
will meet members of the U.S. Treasury and Wall Street traders in
Washington next week as a first step toward enabling the two countries
to enter the international bond market.
</P>
<P>
Jimnah Mbaru, Chairman of the Nairobi Stock Exchange, and
Deputy Governor of Kenya's Central Bank Nzioki Kibua, are among
the African officials to attend the U.S.-African conference over
credit ratings for the sub-Saharan countries, the weekly East
African reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Richard Rubin and Wall Street traders
will meet the African officials between April 20 and 21 to discuss how
the sub-Sahara African countries can obtain credit ratings from key
assessment firms such as Moody's and Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Uganda, Zimbabwe and Cote d'Ivoire are in a top tier of
African states that should be able to enter global bond markets
in two years, predicts Walter Kansteiner, an investment
advisor and Africa commodities trader.
</P>
<P>
Their ability to obtain the necessary credit ratings will
hinge, however, on the degree of political and financial
stability they demonstrate, said Kansteiner, who will be speaking
at the Washington conference.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the only sub-Saharan country to have received
an "investment-grade" rating from the leading evaluators of
nations' credit-worthiness. Other African states are effectively
shut out of the international bond market.
</P>
<P>
There is no shortage of potential buyers of African sovereign
debt, "but to be able to play in this game, you first have to get
credentials as a player," said Kansteiner, noting that a risk
rating is an essential precondition for investors interested in a
country's sovereign debt.
</P>
<P>
Nations such as Kenya and Uganda that may eventually obtain
credit ratings can expect their sovereign debt to be initially
placed in the junk-bond category, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Set to Tackle Liquidity Crunch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Democrat Party has
agreed to issue four executive decrees to tackle the liquidity
crunch in a bid to bring down the current high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting of ministers in
charge of economic affairs from the Democrat Party on Saturday, a
government source said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But coalition partners have yet to be consulted on the issue,
the source said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Government officials had proposed that the cabinet issue an
executive decree to authorize the Financial Institutions
Development Fund (FIDF) to issue long-term bonds to help limit the
FIDF's borrowing from the short-term financial market.
</P>
<P>
The FIDF has been blamed for mismanagement that was one of the
causes of the economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said last week that the
government was considering the possibility of pushing for four
financial bills, including the one related to the FIDF, when
parliament convenes a special meeting in may.
</P>
<P>
The four decrees, once approved by coalition partners, would
enable the government to issue more bonds in overseas markets and
subsequently prompt capital inflows. They would also allow the
government to act faster to tackle the liquidity crunch, the
source said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
He said the four decrees would be submitted to the cabinet for
re-deliberation and were expected to be issued on April 28.
</P>
<P>
He said the decrees would be ratified by the house during an
extra-parliamentary session in may. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
