<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 08:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Refutes Iraqi Allegations on Jail Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has refuted Iraqi
allegations that Kuwait had rejected an Iraqi proposal inviting
the International Committee for Red Cross (ICRC) to search for
Kuwait's POWs in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Majed Al-Shaheen, deputy chairman of the Kuwait
National Committee for Missing and POWs Affairs, said in a
statement through Kuwait News Agency that Kuwait had welcomed ICRC
efforts to be acquainted with the conditions of prisoners and
detainees in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were in response to press reports that Chairman of
Iraqi National Council Saadoun Hamadi indicated during the ongoing
meeting of the International Parliamentary Union in the Namibian
capital of Windhoek that the allied countries including Kuwait
rejected the Iraqi proposal.
</P>
<P>
"During the meeting in February 1997 of the tripartite
committee, Iraq invited the ICRC to visit the jails in a general
form to get acquainted with the prisoners' state," Al-Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
"At the time, ICRC noted that this matter was a bilateral
issue between Iraq and the ICRC, and it was procedural and was not
related to the tripartite committee or any of its members,"
Al-Shaheen added.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite committee, set up after the Gulf War in 1991,
groups Iraq, the ICRC, and the allied countries that ousted Iraqi
forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled that since February 1997, the ICRC has not
been able to reach any agreement with the Iraqi regime over the
mechanism and conditions of visits to Iraqi prisons.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been the most emotional one hindering
improvement of relations between Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait said that Baghdad still detains 625 Kuwaiti POWs in
Iraqi jails and has frequently urged Iraq to release them, but
Baghdad said those POWs were missing during turmoils in southern
Iraq following the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has insisted that the return of the Kuwaiti POWs is the
top condition for improving its ties with Iraq, saying this is the
most important issue for every individual in Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
