<HEADLINE> 56 Bodies Recovered, 21 Saved in Tanzania Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 56 bodies have
been recovered from a tanzanite mine in north Tanzania's Arusha
Region which buried at least 90 miners after a landslide, the
state-owned Daily News said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government announced that rescue team has saved
21 people trapped in the mine, which collapsed after a downpour
last Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanite is a semi-precious stone unique to Tanzania and is
mined using traditional methods, often few safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Tanzaian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye cut short
his Easter holiday and flew to Arusha. He was accompanied by the
Minister for Energy and Minerals, Abdallah Kigoda, and Arusha
Regional Commissioner, Daniel Njoolay.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye has ordered the mine owners to stop all mining
activities until all bodies were recovered. He also showed
dissatisfaction with the owners who do not even have a list of
their workers, which makes it difficult to identify those who
were missing in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has appealed for pumps to suck out water in
mines and earth moving equipment such as caterpillars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the rescue work have been done by miners who escaped
the disaster and engineers from the Fire Brigade and regional
water department.
</P>
<P>
Rescue has been slowed down because of Easter holidays, making
rescue workers unable to get in touch with companies which have
appropriate equipment.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that stench from rotten bodies at the mine forced
a poorly equipped rescue team reluctant to go ahead with their
task.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people from Arusha and neighboring regions have
come to the mining area in Mererani, 40 km away from the Arusha
town, anxious to know the fate of their relatives, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economist Suggests China Encourage Consumers' Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A professor at Hunan Finance and
Economics College, Zeng Linghua, has suggested that China
encourage consumers' spending to help maintain its economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Zeng says in an article carried by today's Economic Daily that
household spending of the Chinese is 20 to 28 percentage points
lower than those in countries with similar per capita income and
that this low rate is from a lack of demand.
</P>
<P>
He points to two ways to bring the rate up, by increasing the
proportion of resident's income to the country's GDP and by
encouraging consumers' spending in relation to per capita income.
</P>
<P>
As the resident's income in China is about 68 percent of the
country's GDP, or nearly the same as in the developed countries,
it is improper to make it higher, Zeng says.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he adds, China should stimulate consumers' spending
so as to boost its economic growth. The consumers spending to
income rate dropped to 71 percent in 1996 from 1978's 97.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said, to stimulte consumers' spending, priority should be
given to the development of agriculture, animal husbandry and
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The development of the energy industry could also promote the
use of more household electric appliances, especially in rural
areas, the prefessor says.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications and housing should also be given priority,
he says, adding along with this, price reforms and a proper pricing
system are needed.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector should also use interest rates and loans
to stimulate consumers spending, Zeng says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
