<HEADLINE> O'Meara Wins Masters on Final Hole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Mark O'Meara rolled in a
20-foot (6.10-meter) birdie putt on the final hole Sunday to claim
the US Masters title that his close friend Tiger Woods overwhelmed
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The birdie on No.18 gave O'Meara a closing round 67 and a
72-hole total of 279 -- nine strokes higher than the winning score
by Woods last year.
</P>
<P>
The victory marked the first major championship title for the
41-year-old American and also meant that the last 14 major
championships have been won by 14 different people.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Woods, the 22-year-old wonder who shot a
record 18-under par last year and won by a record 12 strokes, only
finished eighth with a 70 and a 285 total.
</P>
<P>
The American duo David Duval and Fred Couples shared the second
place at 280. Jim Furyk was fourth at 281, with Paul Azinger at
282 and Nicklaus and David Toms tied for sixth place at 283.
</P>
</TEXT>
