<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With South African Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, in a
meeting with South Africa's Vice-president Thabo Mbeki this
morning, said that the establishing of diplomatic relations
between China and South Africa was a milestone in the history of
relations between the two.
</P>
<P>
China and South Africa are developing countries without
fundamental conflict of interests and with many common interests,
Jiang said, and China has consistently supported the struggle of
the African people for national independence, especially of the
South African people in their fight against racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
It is very important for developing countries to increase
solidarity, he said, and China is willing to develop relations
with South Africa with mutual trust, sincere friendship, and
all-round cooperation and is willing to increase exchanges and
cooperation to promote the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that South Africa is a very important country in Africa
and has a very good foundation for economic development.
</P>
<P>
The new South Africa has had remarkable results in national
construction, he added, and has played a positive role in
international affairs, especially in African affairs, showing that
the new leaders are capable of leading their people in building a
better country.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said that after establishing diplomatic ties, South
Africa has placed great importance to relations with China and is
willing to establish long-term cooperative relations of mutual
trust with China.
</P>
<P>
He said that South Africa is also willing to play a positive
role in regional and international affairs, and that he hopes the
two countries will strengthen cooperation in this.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki arrived in Beijing on Friday and is the first top South
African leader to visit China since the two countries established
diplomatic relations on January 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
