<HEADLINE> Quanzhou-Xiamen Expressway in East China Operating Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Quanzhou-Xiamen expressway in
east China's Fujian province is operating successfully since it
was put into service last December.
</P>
<P>
The 81.4-km-long expressway, the first in the province, was
built with 2.78 billion yuan, including 140 million U.S. dollars
in World Bank loans. The idea to build the road was proposed in
1982, but the project was not launched until 1994.
</P>
<P>
Internationally accepted measures were introduced in the
construction of the expressway.
</P>
<P>
During the construction, the designers and builders paid
special attention to environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's expressways will be extended to 430 kilometers by the
end of this century to link Fuzhou, Putian, Quanzhou, Xiamen and
Zhangzhou, the five largest industrial cities in the province.
</P>
<P>
By then, the province is expected to be connected with
Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces to the north and Guangdong Province
to the south.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
