<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Doctors Recommend Children to Wear Eye Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- American doctors strongly
recommend school children to wear eye protection for school and
community sports.
</P>
<P>
The American Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO), declaring April to
be "Sports Eye Safety Month," said Sunday that it believes eye
protection made of thick, tough polycarbonate plastic should be
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
Doctors link the need for eye protection to the need for helmets
for bicyclists and others engaged in sports that keep them on the
move.
</P>
<P>
The American Academy of Pediatrics also said the plastic guard
should be required particularly for those with eye injuries or with
only one functional eye.
</P>
<P>
Sports-related eye injuries have more than doubled over the past
three years, to 100,000 cases a year, AAO pointed out. Of those
injuries, 90 percent could have been prevented with proper eyewear, it
said, calling for 3-millimeter-thick polycarbonate goggles fitted by a
professional, such as an optician.
</P>
<P>
A serious eye injury can cost 12,000 U.S. dollar in the United
States, said John Jeffers, Chairman of AAO's Committee on Eye
Safety and Sports, adding that goggles fitted by a skilled
optician can cost 50 to 100 dollar each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
