<HEADLINE> Yunnan Becomes Leading Coffee Producer in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics show that
southwest China's Yunnan Province has become the leading coffee
producer in the country, with its total acreage of coffee reaching
7,466.7 hectares, or 65 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The total coffee output of the province stands at 4,000 tons,
accounting for 82 percent of the national total. Last year, the
province earned three million US dollars from coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
The province's output of coffee is expected to increase at an
average 25 percent yearly, which means 1,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the province's largest coffee
plant, coffee trees growing three to four years are capable of
yielding fruits, which lay a solid foundation for the increase in
its output.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan boasts both favorable climate and geological conditions
for growing coffee, with a growing history of 100 years.
</P>
<P>
The province now has established 20 coffee production bases and
more than 100 coffee farms.
</P>
<P>
Other coffee producers in the country include Guangdong and
Hainan provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
