<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: New Nepali PM Girija Prasad Koirala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Girija Prasad Koirala,
president and parliamentary leader of the Nepali Congress, was
appointed Sunday by King Birendra as new prime minister of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
For 73-year-old Koirala, the premiership is nothing new. He
took office in May 1991 as the Kingdom's first popularly elected
prime minister in 30 years. And his brothers Matrika Prasad
Koirala and Bishweshwar Prasad Koirala were also prime ministers
of Nepal in the 1950s and the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
G.P. Koirala began his political career while working at a jute
mill in Biratnagar of eastern Nepal. He participated in the first
industrial strike held in the mill in 1947.
</P>
<P>
He led the labor movement in Biratnagar after the dissolution
of the multi-party system in Nepal in 1960. That year he was
arrested and imprisoned under the State Offense Act for seven
years. He went on a hunger strike in jail for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Three years after he was released from jail, G.P. Koirala was
arrested again under the Security Act. Later he exiled himself to
India until 1979.
</P>
<P>
Koirala held the post of youth leader of the NC for many years.
In 1976, he was elected the party's general secretary at a party
conference held in India.
</P>
<P>
His active involvement in armed struggle against the partyless
Panchayat system in place for three decades culminated in the
people's movement in February 1990.
</P>
<P>
The movement forced King Birendra to abolish the Panchayat
system and restore the multi-party democratic system in the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the first free elections in May 1991, Koirala was
elected member of the House of Representatives and his party won a
clear majority. He assumed the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In March 1994, he resigned and recommended mid-term polls after
losing a key vote in parliament. The polls in November 1994
resulted in a hung parliament where no single party holds a
majority, which in turn leads to the emergence of coalition
politics in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
But Koirala was reelected member of the House of
Representatives in the elections. And in May 1996, he was elected
president of the NC at the 9th general convention of the party.
</P>
<P>
The new prime minister believes in "nation, nationalism and
democratic socialism advocated by the NC," and "dedication to
duty, firmness in devotion and commitment to stabilize democracy."
</P>
<P>
He remains single after his wife died many years ago. He has
one daughter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Growing Vegetables at South Pole Without Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are raising
their own vegetables at a research station at the South Pole
without using soil as a means of solving the vegetable problem
there.
</P>
<P>
Xia Limin, a secretary of the Antarctic Investigation Office
who recently returned from the station, says that before going
there in 1996 he was trained is soilless cultivation technology at
the Chinese Academy of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
What this generally means is the use of hydroponics, although
other methods are being studied, and through his experiments, Xia
managed to sprout radishes and peas from seeds in four big basins
where a nutrient solution was used. The source of light was
fluorescent lamps.
</P>
<P>
The seeds sprouted after several days and Xia says that he
could get five kilograms of vegetables in ten days. In the past
two years, he has grown 250 kilograms of vegetables, and has had a
sprouting rate of more than 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
He also says that the vegetables are fresh tasting and have no
pollution. By now, all personnel at the station have acquired the
appropriate technology for this.  
</P>
</TEXT>
