<HEADLINE> Foreigners Allowed to Own Total Stakes of Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has decided to allow
foreigners to have total ownership of Thai mutual fund companies
in a bid to clear up stakes held by defunct finance firms.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Financial Restructuring Authority has been seeking
ways to dispose equity in mutual funds held by the 56 firms closed
down last December, said Chalee Chantanayingyong, director of
Thailand's department of the Investment management supervision.
</P>
<P>
Among funds said to be of interest to foreigners is Gs Asset
Management, in which the largest stake is held by General Finance,
one of the closed firms, Monday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
M. L. Pakakaew Boonliang, chief executive of Gs Asset
Management, said although foreigners were interested in local
mutual funds, she felt more comfortable with Thai rather than
foreign investors because marketing focused on the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
But funds with major foreign equity could have the advantage of
access to comprehensive information and analyses from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Changes in the company's rules on equity sales required
approval from shareholders and the restructuring authority.
</P>
