<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Celebrates Traditional New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka Monday takes on a
festive mood when the majority Sinhalese and Tamils celebrate the
traditional New Year (April 13-14) and observe their age-old
customs in the island country.
</P>
<P>
The whole country, especially rural areas, is reverberated with
beating of drums and lighting of fire crackers.
</P>
<P>
The cooking of milk rice, the wearing of new cloths, greetings
to the elders in the family and the feeling of friendship towards
all, are common to both the Sinhalese and Tamil people.
</P>
<P>
However, the Sri Lankan army and police have tightened security
in the whole country, particularly in the capital city Colombo in
a bid to prevent possible Tamil rebel attacks during the new year.
</P>
<P>
The army and police have reportedly launched a massive joint
search operations against the rebels in Colombo and its suburbs
during the past several days.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga Sunday said the
celebration of the New Year was a "strong unifying thread in the
fabric of relationship between the Sinhalese and Tamil people."
</P>
<P>
"We must end the war by unifying our fractured land," she said
in her New Year message, adding that "we must go forward on the
path of peace."
</P>
</TEXT>
