<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Underground Reservoirs Built in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Building underground reservoirs
has become an effective way for Longkou City, east China's
Shandong Province, to fight drought.
</P>
<P>
The city, located in a coastal hilly area on the Jiaodong
Peninsula, has an annual water shortage of 47 million cubic
meters. On the other hand, floods during the rainy season have
rushed through the Huangshui River, the only water source for the
city, into the sea without being used.
</P>
<P>
To make better use of the water sources, Longkou city invested
over 60 million yuan (7.22 million US dollars) in building a
series of water-control projects.
</P>
<P>
These projects include a 160,000 square meter underground
reservoir which is six kilometers long and 26.7 meters deep, with
a storage capacity of over 50 million cubic meters; over 2,500
pump wells, 488 ditches, 733 water storage basins along both sides
of the upper reaches of the Huangshui River and four dykes at the
middle reaches of the river. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0168 </DOCNO>
