<HEADLINE> Beijing Symphony Orchestra to Employ Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Symphony Orchestra
plans to employ foreign musicians to improve its overall
performing level, according to the orchestra's chief conductor.
</P>
<P>
Tan Lihua said that his orchestra is weak in wind instruments,
which is a common problem for most Chinese symphony orchestras.
</P>
<P>
"Especially with the French horn," Tan said, "Chinese people
play such musical instruments just like foreigners playing Chinese
Dizi (bamboo flute)."
</P>
<P>
To date, the orchestra has found several musicians in east
European countries and they are expected to come in the second
half of the year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for a Chinese music group to employ
foreign musicians though for many years, some Chinese music groups
have invited foreign musicians as guest players in particular
performances.
</P>
<P>
Monthly pay for each foreign musician is 1,000 US dollars in
addition to free housing and other welfare services.
</P>
<P>
"Sure, I hope that the world's best musicians will come to join
us," Tan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
