<HEADLINE> South China Province's Banking Sector Going More Electronic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province in south
China is stepping up efforts to make its banking sector more
electronic to provide better and quicker services.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had issued 7.6 million
financial cards of various kinds, an increase of 40 percent from
1996.
</P>
<P>
Over the past seven years, the financial sector in Guangdong
had injected more than three billion yuan to computerize its working
systems, involving 500 sets of large and medium-sized computers,
100,000 personal computers, 2,700 ATMs, and 20,000 POS.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the province opened inter-bank ATM services, and now
95 percent of the local ATMs have entered the network and linked
up with 70 banks in Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it set up China's largest inter-bank POS network. By
now, some 800 POS have been connected to the system, covering 500
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to issue 20 million financial cards by the
end of the century to make up 20 percent of the country's total,
with annual trade volume expected at 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it will have 30,000 POS at that time to cover
hotels of three-star and above, shopping markets that have
5,000-square-meter business area and 100 million yuan of annual
sales. 
</P>
