<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Against Interference in Its Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia is opposed to
interference in its internal affairs by some big powers, a senior
official said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Countries which like to interfere, out of their own interests,
in the internal affairs of small nations should know that the
people of the small are strongly against it, said Dragan Tomic,
chairman of the National Assembly of the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
Tomic made the remarks on Radio Pozarevac before the referendum
in Serbia scheduled for April 23, which was initiated by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
In the address, Tomic said that some big powers do not take the
interests of small countries into account when setting up a
so-called new world order aimed at dominating the destiny of the
small ones.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav people do not like them doing so, Tomic stressed.
</P>
<P>
The coming referendum in the Serb Republic is the right
occasion for the people of Yugoslavia to maintain the country's
sovereignty and independence, the chairman added.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians in Kosovo in the Serb Republic, who had
refused to hold talks with the Serb government since the breakout
of conflicts with the Serb police in February, now agreed to sit
at the table with the government on March 27 on the precondition
that international coordinators participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, the authorities of both Yugoslavia and the Serb
Repubic are opposed to the internationalization of the Kosovo
issue, which they consider an internal affair of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly of Serbia is set to hold the referendum
on April 23 to decide whether to accept international mediation in
the Kosovo issue. 
</P>
