<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funeral Reform Deepening in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's funeral reform has
entered a new stage since the State Council issued a set of
regulations strenthening funeral management in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China has all along stressed cremation in reform, which now has
been popularized from the urban areas to the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
For thousands of years, Chinese people have used to burying of
the deceased remains underground, and this has occupied much
land. However, China now has to feed 22 percent of the world's
population with only 7 percent of the world's arable land.
</P>
<P>
In view of the problem, many senior Chinese leaders signed to
be cremated after death in April 1956, promoting cremation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
To date, Shandong, Jiangsu, Liaoning, Heilongjiang, Beijing,
Tianjin and Shanghai have become the first group of provinces and
municipalities in the country to push cremation among all
residents. In 1997, the cremation rate in the country reached 36.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the 1989-1997 period show that cremation had
saved 120,000 hectares of land, 10 million cubic meters of timber
and one billion yuan (120 million US dollars) of funeral fees.
</P>
<P>
Many ways have been used to bury the ashes of the dead, such as
building ash walls, corridors, halls, tombs and scattering the
ashes of the dead into the sea.
</P>
<P>
Many local governments have extended great efforts in
mobilizing people to change their traditional burying habbits,
with over 100,000 cemeteries having been established in the
country's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 420,000 grassroots organizations in charge of funeral
activities are playing a key role in promoting the implementation
of cremation and good customs of funerals throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Hydropower Plant Still Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's oldest hydropower plant,
which has a history of 88 years, generated 7.8 million kwh of
electricity last year, and is now still doing well.
</P>
<P>
"The Shilongba Hydropower Plant is nothing in history, and
particularly so in terms of its power generating
capacity. However, it represents China's self-reliant efforts,"
said Zhang Junfeng, director of the plant, which is located in
Yunnan province, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the century, the French colonialists wanted
to build a hydropower plant near Dianchi Lake, the largest in
Yunnan. But the demand met with strong opposition from the local
people.
</P>
<P>
In 1910, the local people pooled money and began to build the
plant on their own. It took more than 400 workers three months to
transport equipment imported from Germany to the lake side, only
a four-kilometer distance.
</P>
<P>
Two years later, two generating units went into operation,
providing electricity for 3,000 light bulbs. Local residents
crowded to have a look at the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
During the anti-Japanese war (1937-1945), the plant served as
the power source for armament production and air defence warning,
and survived four raids by Japanese fighters.
</P>
<P>
The early 480-kw capacity of the plant has been expanded to the
current 7,040 kw. In 1957, it became the country's first to use
Chinese-made water turbogenerators.
</P>
<P>
Now the plant has been listed as one of the province's
protected historical sites, and more than 50,000 people from
at home and abroad have visited it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
