<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Flex Muscles in Market-Oriented Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Xu Cailian, a woman in northwest
China's Yan'an city, one of China's major revolutionary bases,
sells some 1,400 tons of grain annually to various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
She is one of the 5,044 women in the city that have made a name
by involving in different trades.
</P>
<P>
The woman started her business years ago by collecting locally
unmarketable but abundant wild apricots, and selling them
elsewhere. She made a fortune out of it. Later, she turned to
cereals transaction.
</P>
<P>
The city's women federation is attributable to the progress. In
the past few years, it held more than 34,000 training classes on
practical techniques, involving 163,000 women, 111,000 of whom
have learned to use one or two such techniques, and another 1,096
have become farmer technicians.
</P>
<P>
The federation also sponsored 23 training classes on high and
new technologies, and sent 22 women to university. In addition,
1,399 others are attending lessons by an agricultural
correspondence college.
</P>
<P>
The fact that better-educated women do a better work
is inspiring illiterate ones. And the federation's effort in this
regard has helped 25,000 women become literate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
