<HEADLINE> Karadzic Not to Surrender Himself: Serb Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Radovan Karadzic, Bosnia's
most-wanted war crime suspect, is not to surrender himself to a
U.N. tribunal, according to a Serb leader close to Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member of Bosnia's tripartite
presidency, told reporters on Saturday in Pale, outside Sarajevo,
that Western media reports of Karadzic's imminent surrender were
simply rubbish.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic, 52, who has not been seen in public since mid-1996, is
wanted by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia in The Hague (ICTY), together with his army commander,
Gen Ratko Mladic, for crimes of war, against humanity and
genocide.
</P>
<P>
The Belgrade-based newspaper Vecernje Novosti Sunday quoted
Krajisnik as saying "All claims that Karadzic will surrender
himself have no foundation."
</P>
<P>
"They are simply speculation," Krajisnik said, following a
meeting with U.S. Ambassador to Bosnia-Hercegovina, Richard
Kavzlarich, who hoped Karadzic would give himself up for trial
before the ICTY.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know where he is and I have no contact with him,"
said Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
However, Krajisnik admitted that he had contacts with
Karadzic's wife Ljiljana Zelen.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reported Karadzic received a lot of letters every
day from the Bosnian Serb entity Republika Srpska, Yugoslavia and
other parts of the world. People asked Karadzic in their letters
not to surrender and hundreds of supporters volunteered to come to
Karadzic's hideaway to protect him, president of former Republika
Srpska. 
