<HEADLINE> China Increasing Investment In Infrastructures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to increase
investment in infrastructures as a way to promote domestic demand
and ensure the planned eight-percent economic growth rate this
year, "Economic Daily" reports today.
</P>
<P>
It says that 10.1 billion yuan will be added to large and
medium-sized railway projects this year and 245 billion yuan over
the next five years, instead of the 100 billion yuan as was
previously planned.
</P>
<P>
In highway construction, 500 billion yuan will be spent for the
next three years. This year's amount will be 160 billion yuan,
instead of the original 120 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China planned to build at least 1,000 km of expressways over
the next three years, but now plans to spend enough for building
at least 4,000 km of expressways.
</P>
<P>
Investment in postal and telecommunications projects for the
same period will also be up, to 150 billion yuan from the
previously-planned 130 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The state has decided to add 120 billion yuan for the period to
sewage and garbage treatment in cities and 110 billion yuan for
water projects to solve the water problems of 100 cities.
</P>
<P>
The increased infrastructure funds will come from domestic bank
loans, limited use of long-term bond issues, public listing of
some highway and bridge projects, an increase of certain water
fees and railway transport fees, and from more overseas and
special coal, power, transportation, and telecommunications
funds. 
</P>
