<HEADLINE> Death Tolls in Hunger Rise in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 36 people have died of
hunger while the drought brought about by the El Nino phenomenon
persisted in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star reported on Monday that health officials in
southern Mindanao have warned of more deaths among people who were
forced to eat poisonous tubers due to the food crisis.
</P>
<P>
Health official Tahir Salaik was quoted as saying that "many
deaths among indigenous communities even remain unreported."
</P>
<P>
Many children in rural areas in the region are very weak and
are experiencing malnutrition, the report added.
</P>
<P>
"There are many children who are very weak. I don't think they
can recover without due attention soon," said Mahilinde
Zambarrano, another health official working in the region.
</P>
<P>
Many provinces in Mindanao are reeling from the El Nino-induced
drought. Agricultural crops have been wiped out, resulting in
shortage of food supply. The severe lack of food drove tribal folk
to eat a type of yam which is toxic when not prepared properly.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos has ordered the release of 23 million
pesos (some 605,263 U.S. dollars). However, food aid has only been
trickling to the hunger-stricken region, the report said. 
</P>
