<DOCNO> XIE19980413.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's Guangzhou City Plans Public Land Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, will auction off the use rights for
two plots of land next June, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Heralding it as an experimental move, local officials said that
they would strive to conduct the auction professionally and with
great caution.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the two parcels of land, each with
an area of about 53,000 sq m, are designed for developing
open-market residential buildings and have been taken over by the
Guangzhou Land Development Center.
</P>
<P>
One parcel is located south of Industrial Road in southern
Guangzhou and the other is west of the Airport Road in
northwestern Guangzhou. Demolishing existing buildings, removing
debris and leveling the ground have been completed on the two
pieces of land thus far, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The sale will give owners use right of the land for a term of
70 years.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Huasui Auction Co., auctioneer in this move, said
it would operate the whole procedure according to the country's
Auction Law and standard international practice.
</P>
<P>
"Opening bids for the lands are still being evaluated," the
newspaper quoted a local land official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official disclosed that organizers expect to earn at least
200 million yuan from the sale of the parcel in the northwestern
part of the city. This patch will be divided into four to six
parts and be auctioned separately in a bid to get immediate
payment.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the auction was made after a full
investigation into the market, banks and real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
Replacing free land distribution that marked the nation's
planned economy, Guangzhou started to sell its land use right
first in 1979, in cooperation with a Hong Kong real estate
developers. Cost of the land was counted as part of the
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
