<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Kills 116 People in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Dengue fever, a cholera-like
disease, has killed 116 people and infected 3,009 others in ten
regencies in Indonesia's South Sumatra province, since the
beginning of this year, a local official said.
</P>
<P>
Along with an American naval research unit, a team of the
provincial health office has conducted a research work to find out
how the infectious disease has spread, chief of the assistance
section of the provincial health office Rozali Namursa was quoted
as saying Sunday by the local press.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute tropical disease transmitted by
mosquitoes, leaves its victims with fever, rash and severe pains
in the joints and back.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Jakarta health official said Sunday that the death
toll in the city's dengue fever outbreak has reached 31 this year
as of last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The virus, to which children are most susceptible, has
hospitalized at least 2,930 people during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Some experts have expressed their fears that a dengue fever
epidemic is likely to occur in other parts of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
