<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decade-long Opening Forges China's Youngest Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Largely by opening to the outside,
Hainan Province in south China has accumulated strength over the
past decade for economic take-off.
</P>
<P>
China's largest special economic zone (SEZ), the island
province has been making efforts to invite capital, professionals,
and technologies from overseas in developing its economy.
</P>
<P>
During the period, it used 7.5 billion US dollars and 50
billion yuan of overseas and domestic investment, accounting for
70 percent of the total fixed asset investment, government sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The province now has over 10,000 joint ventures, which in
some places contribute 70 percent to local industrial and
commercial taxes.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has been directing investment into its priority
development areas. As a result, 75 percent of coming capital in
the past four years went to newly emerging industries,
high-efficient tropical agriculture, tourism, and other
infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The youngest province, which has been formed in 1988, has
established economic and trade relations with more than 60
countries and regions, and imported large amount of advanced
technologies and management expertise.
</P>
<P>
Some multinational corporations, such as DuPond and Daewoo,
have also opened businesses on the island.
</P>
<P>
The province also serves as a pilot area for China to try new
policies. The 30-square-kilometer Yangpu Economic Development
Zone, for example, initiated the practice of foreign investors
building infrastructure by signing land-use contracts with the
province.
</P>
<P>
A SEZ compensation regulation on investment in infrastructure
has greatly encouraged investors to go into the power, highways
and airports sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
