<HEADLINE> Philippines Cuts Dollar Amount for Foreign Travels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has approved a 150 percent reduction in the amount of
U.S. dollars one person can take out of the country, Philippine
Daily Inquirer reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which would start at the end of this month or in
early May, is designed to prevent a further depreciation of the
peso against the dollar by retaining dwindling supplies of the
greenback, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that "necessary documentation" would be needed for
anyone to bring out more than 10,000 dollars after the scheme is
implemented.
</P>
<P>
The current limit on dollars that can be brought out by one
person stands at 25,000.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the financial crisis last July, the peso has
depreciated by half in its value and currently stands at around 38
pesos a dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
