<HEADLINE> Schumacher Ends McLaren Dominance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Double world champion
Michael Schumacher ended McLaren's dominance of two previous
Formula One races on Sunday as he achieved the 28th victory of his
career in the Argentine Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The German's first triumph of the season boosted him up to
the second in the drivers' standings after Finn Mika Hakkinen of
McLaren.
</P>
<P>
For McLaren, the result ended a run of three successive one-two
finishes -- the final race of 1997 and the two opening grands prix
this year in Australia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher finished in a time of one hour 48 minutes 36.175
seconds, 22.9 seconds clear of second-placed Hakkinen in the
leading McLaren. His Ferrari team mate Eddie Irvine was third, a
further 34 seconds adrift.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Wurz of Austria finished fourth in a Benetton, Jean
Alesi fifth for Sauber and David Coulthard sixth in the second
McLaren.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine race was an incident-filled one marred with
several collisions. Even Schumacher was among the spinners as he
collided with Briton Coulthard, but he survived the incident and
brought his car home triumphantly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
