<HEADLINE> Paula Jones to Decide Whether to Appeal This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Paula Jones, whose harassment
lawsuit against U.S. President Bill Clinton was dismissed by a
federal judge on April 1, is planning to announce whether she will
appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Jones will likely reveal her decision Thursday,
spokeswoman Susan Carpenter McMillan said Sunday, according to
reports.
</P>
<P>
McMillan declined to say whether she would appeal. Mrs. Jones
was expected to announce the decision herself.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Jones, 31, claimed that Clinton propositioned her in an
Arkansas hotel room in 1991 when she was a state worker. Clinton
said he doesn't recall ever meeting her and has firmly denied
anything improper happened.
</P>
<P>
If Mrs. Jones does appeal, her case would go before 8th Circuit
Court of Appeals in St. Louis, the same court that overruled Judge
Susan Webber Wright in 1996 by saying the sexual harassment case
could go to trial while Clinton is president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton's private attorney has urged Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr to refer his investigation into Whitewater
figure David Hale to the Justice Department because of an alleged
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
Presidential attorney David Kendall, in a five-page letter to
Starr, cited links between the independent counsel and
conservative groups that may have financially supported Hale.
Kendall also accused Starr of not being impartial because he
relied heavily on Hale's testimony to convict Clinton's former
business partners, Susan and the late James McDougal.
</P>
<P>
Kendall stressed that handing the matter over to Justice would
not affect Starr's integrity or independence and would in fact
"increase public confidence in the outcome of the investigation,
whatever it is." 
</P>
</TEXT>
