<HEADLINE> Blair, Mitchell Warn N.Irish Violence to Come </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and Northern Ireland peace talks chairman George Mitchell Sunday
expressed concern that there might be some violence in the
province over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement reached Friday must be approved by separate
referendums in Northern Ireland and Ireland on May 22. Although
the Ulster Unionist Party, the main pro-British Protestant group,
approved the peace deal Saturday, some breakaway republican groups
have denounced the agreement while Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the Irish Republican Army, is still studying the deal.
</P>
<P>
"There will be people who don't want to make the changes
necessary, who are going to try to do everything they can to try
to stop this agreement, and we've got to have the people of vision
triumph over that," Blair was reported as telling reporters in
Spain, where he is on a short holiday.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. senator Mitchell also warned that extremists may
try to scupper the deal in the run-up to the referendum next
month.
</P>
<P>
"There are people on both sides who want to disrupt this
process who are committed to the way of violence and I expect they
will step up their activities between now and the date of the
referendum and thereafter," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But it's been going on a long time and people recognize it for
what it is, so my hope is that it won't destabilize the process,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
It is now crucial for the British and Irish governments to
ensure a "yes" vote in the two referendums on May 22, for a "no"
vote in either one would doom the deal reached after 22 months of
hard talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
