<HEADLINE> Israeli Policies Obstruct Mideast Peace: Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- An Arab member of the Israeli
Knesset (Parliament) said here on Sunday that the policies of
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu are the hurdles to
peace-making in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"No peace can be achieved within the Likud-led government's
policies ... Time is now ripe for unveiling the Israeli premier's
maneuvers," Saleh Tarif told reporters after a meeting with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Tarif, who heads the Internal Affairs Committee of the Israeli
Knesset, described as "a political ploy" Israel's recent offer to
withdraw from south Lebanon with security guarantees from Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Israel agreed on April 1 to accept the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425, which calls for unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon. But in the meantime, it demanded security
arrangements be worked out with Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate their stances on
all key issues, have rejected the offer, insisting that the Jewish
state pull out of Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Tarif said that Netanyahu is trying to use the proposal to
divert attention from the real crisis facing the peace talks with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He warned of the deteriorating economic conditions in the
Palestinian self-rule territories, noting that efforts should be
made to push forward the peace process to avert an explosion of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks came to a standstill March
1997 when Israel broke ground for the construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as
capital of their future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
