<HEADLINE> Egypt Sends Medicines to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A 40-truck Egyptian convoy carrying
medicines and medical equipment worth 14 million pounds (4.12
million U.S. dollars) left here Sunday for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The supplies are sent to Iraq under the second stage of the
U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food agreement, which allows Iraq to sell 2.1
billion dollars worth of oil every six months to purchase food,
medicines and other basic necessities. The convoy was expected to
arrive in Baghdad in five days.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation has recently visited Baghdad and held
talks with Iraqi officials on further medical supplies to the
country under the current third stage of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Egyptian Pharmaceuticals Holding Company Galal
Ghourab said the company has so far received orders to send to
Iraq medical supplies worth 14 million pounds (4.12 million
dollars) under the third stage of the deal.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to ease the worsening economic situation in the
country caused by crippling U.N. sanctions, the U.N. Security
Council voted unanimously in February to allow Baghdad to increase
the amount of oil it can sell from 2.1 billion dollars to 5.2
billion dollars over six months.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed against Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990
can not be lifted until Iraq has complied with the U.N.
resolutions demanding it to destroy all weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
