<HEADLINE> Clinton Expected to Visit Ireland, N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Northern Ireland peace
mediator George Mitchell and a congressman said Sunday that they
expected President Bill Clinton to visit Ireland and Northern
Ireland to generate support for the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Peter King, a New York Republican member of the House of
Representatives, told the Fox News Sunday television program that
he thought Clinton intended to go.
</P>
<P>
"I think he should definitely go to Belfast and Dublin. I think
he will; that's my understanding from people I've spoken to that
right now his current intention is to go," King said.
</P>
<P>
However, a White House spokesman said no decision had been made
on the visit, but the president was considering the trip.
</P>
<P>
Ireland and the British-rule Northern Ireland were to hold
separate referendum on May 22 to decide the fate of the peace deal
announced on Friday. A "no" vote in either plebiscite would doom
the delicate compromise proposals.
</P>
<P>
The agreement seeks to end three decades of sectarian strife in
Northern Ireland by altering constitutional arrangements for the
province.
</P>
<P>
George Mitchell, the U.S. mediator for the Northern Ireland
talks, said he hoped the president would visit, but he added that
Clinton was waiting to see what British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern thought best.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the TV program "this week" of the American
Broadcasting Company (ABC), Mitchell heralded Clinton's role in
brokering the peace pact for Northern Ireland last week and
stressed that all sides must now ensure ultimate success of the
deal to end three decades of sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement really doesn't finalize peace. It creates the
opportunity for peace and reconciliation," Mitchell said. "It's a
good first step, but there's still a long way to go."
</P>
<P>
Mitchell said he believed a return Clinton visit to Northern
Ireland in the coming months would bolster support for the peace
pact before a voter referendum on May 22.
</P>
<P>
Clinton traveled to both Northern Ireland's capital, Belfast,
and Dublin, capital of the Republic of Ireland, in 1995. He is
"the only American president ever to have visited Northern Ireland
while in office," said Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
On May 15, Clinton is visiting Britain to attend the three-day
Birmingham meeting of the Group of Eight, namely the world's seven
major industrialized countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
British media reports said that Clinton might offer millions of
dollars investment in Northern Ireland and provide an economic
incentive for voters to endorse the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
