<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gangs, Violent Crime Rise in U.S. Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Street gangs in schools nearly
doubled and violent crime increased by 25 percent in the United
States in six years from 1989 to 1995, said a government report
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Surveys found that street gangs were spotted in schools by 28.4
percent of students questioned in 1995 compared with 15.3 percent
in 1989, according to the Bureau of Justice Statistics and the
National Center for Education Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, violent crime at school -- physical attacks or a
robbery by force, weapon or threat -- was reported by 4.2 percent
of students in 1995, up 23.5 percent from 3.4 percent in 1989, the
Justice and Education departments said.
</P>
<P>
Learning the facts, U.S. President Bill Clinton called the
findings "unacceptable" and urged Congress to approve initiatives
he offered a year ago to fight against gangs and youth violence.
</P>
<P>
"Gangs -- and the guns, drugs and violence that go with them --
must be stopped from ever reaching the schoolhouse door," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Pascal D. Forgione, Jr., U.S. Commissioner of Education
Statistics, noted that the 0.8 percentage points represented an
increase of about 270,000 students and the gang increase came in
every type of community.
</P>
<P>
In central cities, students reporting street gangs rose from
24.8 percent to 40.7 percent; in suburbs, from 14.0 percent to
26.3 percent; and in non-metropolitan areas, from 7.8 percent to
19.9 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that violent crime by juveniles peaked in
1994 and has declined for two years since then. Arrests of
teenagers for violent crimes dropped 2.9 percent in 1995 and 9.2
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Gangs in schools also have decreased in the last couple of
years. In 1993, a study found 35 percent of students saying
"fighting" gangs were present in their schools.
</P>
<P>
On other aspects, the survey found in 1995 that 65.3 percent of
students reported that marijuana, cocaine, crack, uppers or
downers were available at school compared with 63.2 percent in
1989.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 survey also found that about one in 20 students said
they saw another students with a gun at school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
